1
00:01:25,110 --> 00:01:27,903
I owe everything to George Bailey.

2
00:01:28,321 --> 00:01:30,197
Help him, dear Father.

3
00:01:30,573 --> 00:01:33,617
Joseph, Jesus and Mary,

4
00:01:33,886 --> 00:01:36,328
help my friend Mr. Bailey.

5
00:01:36,788 --> 00:01:39,414
Help my son George tonight.

6
00:01:40,249 --> 00:01:42,117
He never thinks about himself, God.

7
00:01:42,217 --> 00:01:43,952
That's why he's in trouble.

8
00:01:44,052 --> 00:01:45,212
George is a good guy.

9
00:01:46,381 --> 00:01:47,623
Give him a break, God.

10
00:01:47,723 --> 00:01:49,833
I love him, dear Lord.

11
00:01:49,933 --> 00:01:51,802
Watch over him tonight.

12
00:01:52,261 --> 00:01:53,587
Please, God.

13
00:01:53,687 --> 00:01:55,964
Something's the matter with Daddy.

14
00:01:56,064 --> 00:01:58,350
Please bring Daddy back.

15
00:01:58,935 --> 00:02:00,469
Please bring Daddy home.

16
00:02:00,569 --> 00:02:02,771
Watch over him tonight.

17
00:02:03,147 --> 00:02:05,440
Please bring Daddy back.

18
00:02:09,320 --> 00:02:11,355
Hello, Joseph. Trouble?

19
00:02:11,455 --> 00:02:14,024
Looks like we'll have
to send someone down.

20
00:02:14,124 --> 00:02:17,194
A lot of people asking for help
for a man named George Bailey.

21
00:02:17,294 --> 00:02:18,821
George Bailey?

22
00:02:18,921 --> 00:02:21,365
Yes. Tonight's his crucial night.
You're right.

23
00:02:21,465 --> 00:02:24,326
We'll have to send someone down
immediately. Whose turn is it?

24
00:02:24,426 --> 00:02:26,753
That's why I came to see you, sir.

25
00:02:26,963 --> 00:02:29,415
It's that clockmaker's turn again.

26
00:02:29,515 --> 00:02:32,751
Oh, Clarence.
Hasn't got his wings yet, has he?

27
00:02:32,851 --> 00:02:34,712
We've passed him up right along.

28
00:02:34,812 --> 00:02:38,257
Because, you know, sir,
he's got the IQ of a rabbit.

29
00:02:38,357 --> 00:02:41,802
Yes, but he's got
the faith of a child. Simple.

30
00:02:41,902 --> 00:02:43,937
Joseph, send for Clarence.

31
00:02:47,233 --> 00:02:48,600
You sent for me, sir?

32
00:02:48,700 --> 00:02:51,729
Yes, Clarence.
A man down on Earth needs our help.

33
00:02:51,829 --> 00:02:53,397
Splendid. Is he sick?

34
00:02:53,497 --> 00:02:55,691
No, worse. He's discouraged.

35
00:02:55,791 --> 00:02:58,360
At exactly 10:45 p.m. Earth time,

36
00:02:58,460 --> 00:03:00,487
that man will be thinking seriously

37
00:03:00,587 --> 00:03:02,531
of throwing away God's greatest gift.

38
00:03:02,631 --> 00:03:06,243
Oh, dear, dear, his life?
Then I've only an hour to dress.

39
00:03:06,343 --> 00:03:07,536
What are they wearing now?

40
00:03:07,636 --> 00:03:10,748
You will spend that hour
getting acquainted with George Bailey.

41
00:03:10,848 --> 00:03:13,834
Sir, if I should accomplish this mission,

42
00:03:13,934 --> 00:03:17,379
I mean, might I perhaps win my wings?

43
00:03:17,479 --> 00:03:19,923
I've been waiting
for over 200 years now, sir,

44
00:03:20,023 --> 00:03:21,550
and people are beginning to talk.

45
00:03:21,650 --> 00:03:23,093
What's that book you've got there?

46
00:03:23,193 --> 00:03:25,345
The Adventures of Tom Sawyer.

47
00:03:25,445 --> 00:03:27,805
Clarence, you do a good job
with George Bailey

48
00:03:27,905 --> 00:03:29,223
and you'll get your wings.

49
00:03:29,323 --> 00:03:31,058
Oh, thank you, sir. Thank you.

50
00:03:31,158 --> 00:03:33,895
Poor George. Sit down.

51
00:03:33,995 --> 00:03:35,104
Sit down? What are we...

52
00:03:35,204 --> 00:03:36,898
If you're going to help a man,

53
00:03:36,998 --> 00:03:39,317
you want to know something about him,
don't you?

54
00:03:39,417 --> 00:03:40,902
Well, naturally, of course. I...

55
00:03:41,002 --> 00:03:42,286
Now, keep your eyes open.

56
00:03:43,163 --> 00:03:44,280
See the town?

57
00:03:44,380 --> 00:03:47,033
Where? I don't see a thing.

58
00:03:47,133 --> 00:03:49,952
Oh, I forgot.
You haven't got your wings yet.

59
00:03:50,052 --> 00:03:53,005
Now, look, I'll help you out.
Concentrate.

60
00:03:53,715 --> 00:03:55,458
Begin to see something?

61
00:03:55,558 --> 00:03:58,260
Why, yes. This is amazing.

62
00:03:58,386 --> 00:04:00,922
If you ever get your wings,
you'll see all by yourself.

63
00:04:01,022 --> 00:04:02,757
Oh, wonderful.

64
00:04:02,857 --> 00:04:05,551
Yay! Yippee!

65
00:04:05,651 --> 00:04:07,637
Okay, boys, let's go.

66
00:04:07,737 --> 00:04:09,388
Hey, who's that?

67
00:04:09,488 --> 00:04:11,307
That's your problem. George Bailey.

68
00:04:11,407 --> 00:04:12,475
A boy?

69
00:04:12,575 --> 00:04:15,603
That's him when he was 12
back in 1919.

70
00:04:15,703 --> 00:04:19,073
Something happens here
you'll have to remember later on.

71
00:04:19,741 --> 00:04:21,484
Come on, Marty.

72
00:04:21,584 --> 00:04:23,410
Let's go, Marty!

73
00:04:24,246 --> 00:04:25,746
Attaboy, Marty.

74
00:04:26,623 --> 00:04:28,241
Hee-haw!

75
00:04:28,341 --> 00:04:30,292
Let's go, Sam. Hee-haw, Sammy!

76
00:04:31,044 --> 00:04:35,498
Here comes the scare-baby,
my kid brother Harry Bailey.

77
00:04:35,598 --> 00:04:37,299
I'm not scared.

78
00:04:38,426 --> 00:04:39,802
Come on, Harry.

79
00:04:40,220 --> 00:04:41,838
Let's go, Harry!

80
00:04:41,938 --> 00:04:43,256
Come on, Harry!

81
00:04:43,356 --> 00:04:44,507
Come on, Harry!

82
00:04:44,607 --> 00:04:46,600
- Come on, Harry!
- Come on, Harry!

83
00:04:47,269 --> 00:04:48,678
Help, George, help!

84
00:04:48,778 --> 00:04:49,895
Help!

85
00:04:50,981 --> 00:04:53,482
Don't worry, Harry. I'm coming!

86
00:04:53,608 --> 00:04:55,860
- Help!
- Hang on, Harry!

87
00:04:56,027 --> 00:04:58,396
- Help.
- Make a chain, gang.

88
00:04:58,496 --> 00:05:00,990
George saved his brother's life that day,

89
00:05:01,408 --> 00:05:04,785
but he caught a bad cold
which infected his left ear.

90
00:05:05,245 --> 00:05:07,405
Cost him his hearing in that ear.

91
00:05:07,505 --> 00:05:09,782
It was weeks
before he was able to go back

92
00:05:09,882 --> 00:05:13,252
to his after-school job
at old man Gower's drugstore.

93
00:05:14,004 --> 00:05:15,121
Mr. Potter.

94
00:05:15,221 --> 00:05:17,498
Who's that, a king?

95
00:05:17,598 --> 00:05:19,500
That's Henry F. Potter,

96
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:22,970
the richest and meanest man
in the county.

97
00:05:27,141 --> 00:05:29,475
- Hee-haw! Hee-haw!
- Hee-haw! Hee-haw!

98
00:05:30,185 --> 00:05:31,895
Go to work, slave.

99
00:05:32,938 --> 00:05:35,106
Don't worry, we'll take care of it.

100
00:05:36,525 --> 00:05:38,526
Wish I had a million dollars.

101
00:05:39,153 --> 00:05:40,403
Hot dog!

102
00:05:44,283 --> 00:05:46,192
It's me, Mr. Gower. George Bailey.

103
00:05:46,292 --> 00:05:47,256
You're late.

104
00:05:47,356 --> 00:05:48,661
Yes, sir.

105
00:05:56,879 --> 00:05:58,296
Hello, George.

106
00:05:58,631 --> 00:05:59,923
Hello, Mary.

107
00:06:00,466 --> 00:06:01,583
Hello, Violet.

108
00:06:01,683 --> 00:06:03,251
Two cents' worth of shoelaces?

109
00:06:03,351 --> 00:06:04,669
She was here first.

110
00:06:04,769 --> 00:06:06,588
I'm still thinking.

111
00:06:06,688 --> 00:06:07,756
Shoelaces?

112
00:06:07,856 --> 00:06:09,432
Please, Georgie.

113
00:06:09,934 --> 00:06:11,092
I like him.

114
00:06:11,192 --> 00:06:12,928
You like every boy.

115
00:06:13,028 --> 00:06:14,638
What's wrong with that?

116
00:06:14,738 --> 00:06:16,230
Here you are.

117
00:06:17,191 --> 00:06:18,266
Help me down?

118
00:06:18,366 --> 00:06:20,234
Help you down?

119
00:06:26,951 --> 00:06:28,777
Made up your mind yet?

120
00:06:28,877 --> 00:06:30,620
I'll take chocolate.

121
00:06:30,746 --> 00:06:33,414
- With coconuts?
- I don't like coconuts.

122
00:06:33,749 --> 00:06:35,458
You don't like coconuts?

123
00:06:35,751 --> 00:06:38,962
Say, brainless, don't you know
where coconuts come from?

124
00:06:39,588 --> 00:06:40,956
Lookit here.

125
00:06:41,056 --> 00:06:44,258
From Tahiti, the Fiji islands,
the Coral Sea.

126
00:06:44,551 --> 00:06:47,796
A new magazine. I never saw it before.

127
00:06:47,896 --> 00:06:50,390
Of course you never.
Only us explorers can get it.

128
00:06:51,100 --> 00:06:54,894
I've been nominated for membership
in the National Geographic Society.

129
00:06:56,397 --> 00:06:58,306
Is this the ear you can't hear on?

130
00:06:58,406 --> 00:07:02,143
George Bailey,
I'll love you till the day I die.

131
00:07:02,243 --> 00:07:05,146
I'm going out exploring someday.
You watch.

132
00:07:05,246 --> 00:07:08,483
And I'm gonna have a couple of harems
and maybe three or four wives.

133
00:07:08,583 --> 00:07:09,826
Wait and see.

134
00:07:12,746 --> 00:07:16,199
- George. George!
- Yes, sir?

135
00:07:16,299 --> 00:07:18,751
You're not paid to be a canary.

136
00:07:19,086 --> 00:07:20,378
No, sir.

137
00:07:47,739 --> 00:07:50,741
Mr. Gower, do you want something?
Anything?

138
00:07:50,908 --> 00:07:51,950
No.

139
00:07:52,618 --> 00:07:55,287
- Anything I can do back here?
- No.

140
00:07:55,788 --> 00:07:57,197
I'll get them, sir.

141
00:07:57,297 --> 00:08:00,083
Quick, take those capsules
over to Mrs. Blaine.

142
00:08:01,210 --> 00:08:02,494
She's waiting for them.

143
00:08:02,594 --> 00:08:03,920
Yes, sir.

144
00:08:26,527 --> 00:08:28,604
They have the diphtheria there,
haven't they, sir?

145
00:08:28,704 --> 00:08:29,780
Yeah.

146
00:08:30,156 --> 00:08:31,656
Is it a charge, sir?

147
00:08:31,908 --> 00:08:33,325
Yes, George.

148
00:08:33,868 --> 00:08:34,985
Mr. Gower, I...

149
00:08:35,085 --> 00:08:37,496
- Oh, get going.
- Yes, sir.

150
00:09:03,981 --> 00:09:06,183
Avast there, Captain Cook.
Where you heading?

151
00:09:06,283 --> 00:09:08,727
- I've got to see Pop, Uncle Billy.
- Some other time, George.

152
00:09:08,827 --> 00:09:10,604
- It's important.
- There's a squall in there.

153
00:09:10,704 --> 00:09:12,189
It's shaping up into a storm.

154
00:09:12,289 --> 00:09:14,399
- Uncle Billy, telephone.
- Who is it?

155
00:09:14,499 --> 00:09:16,743
- Bank examiner.
- Bank examiner?

156
00:09:17,370 --> 00:09:19,029
I should have called him yesterday.

157
00:09:19,129 --> 00:09:20,747
Switch it inside.

158
00:09:23,042 --> 00:09:24,451
I'm not crying, Mr. Potter.

159
00:09:24,551 --> 00:09:26,370
Well, you're begging.
That's a whole lot worse.

160
00:09:26,470 --> 00:09:28,246
All I'm asking for is 30 days more.

161
00:09:28,346 --> 00:09:29,622
- Pop.
- Just a minute, Son.

162
00:09:29,722 --> 00:09:32,383
Just 30 short days.
I'll dig up that $5,000 somehow.

163
00:09:32,551 --> 00:09:33,876
- Shove me up, shove me up.
- Pop.

164
00:09:33,976 --> 00:09:35,795
- Just a minute.
- Have you put any real pressure

165
00:09:35,895 --> 00:09:38,297
on these people of yours
to pay those mortgages?

166
00:09:38,397 --> 00:09:40,716
Times are bad, Mr. Potter.
A lot of these people are out of work.

167
00:09:40,816 --> 00:09:41,884
Well, then, foreclose.

168
00:09:41,984 --> 00:09:43,636
I can't do that.
These families have children.

169
00:09:43,736 --> 00:09:45,263
- Pop.
- They're not my children.

170
00:09:45,363 --> 00:09:47,265
But they're somebody's children,
Mr. Potter.

171
00:09:47,365 --> 00:09:49,892
Are you running a business
or a charity ward?

172
00:09:49,992 --> 00:09:52,103
- Well, all right...
- Not with my money.

173
00:09:52,203 --> 00:09:54,772
Mr. Potter, what makes you
such a hard-skulled character?

174
00:09:54,872 --> 00:09:56,691
You have no family, no children.

175
00:09:56,791 --> 00:09:58,651
You can't begin
to spend all the money you've got.

176
00:09:58,751 --> 00:10:01,988
I suppose I should give it
to miserable failures

177
00:10:02,088 --> 00:10:05,283
like you and that idiot brother of yours
to spend for me.

178
00:10:05,383 --> 00:10:06,576
He's not a failure!

179
00:10:06,676 --> 00:10:09,495
- You can't say that about my father.
- George, George. Quiet, George.

180
00:10:09,595 --> 00:10:10,913
You're not.
You're the biggest man in town...

181
00:10:11,013 --> 00:10:12,498
- Run along, run along.
- ...bigger than him,

182
00:10:12,598 --> 00:10:14,750
- bigger than everybody.
- Gives you an idea of the Baileys.

183
00:10:14,850 --> 00:10:16,586
Don't let him say that about you, Pop.

184
00:10:16,686 --> 00:10:18,337
All right, Son. All right. Thanks.

185
00:10:18,437 --> 00:10:20,181
I'll talk to you tonight.

186
00:10:27,147 --> 00:10:28,514
What?

187
00:10:28,614 --> 00:10:31,942
Why, that medicine should have
been there an hour ago.

188
00:10:32,444 --> 00:10:34,987
It will be over in five minutes,
Mrs. Blaine.

189
00:10:38,950 --> 00:10:41,194
Where's Mrs. Blaine's box of capsules?

190
00:10:41,294 --> 00:10:42,912
I... You...

191
00:10:43,705 --> 00:10:45,072
Didn't you hear what I said?

192
00:10:45,172 --> 00:10:46,240
Yes, sir. I...

193
00:10:46,340 --> 00:10:48,834
What kind of tricks
are you playing anyway?

194
00:10:50,921 --> 00:10:53,581
Why didn't you deliver them right away?

195
00:10:53,681 --> 00:10:55,208
Don't you know that boy's very sick?

196
00:10:55,308 --> 00:10:56,751
You're hurting my sore ear.

197
00:10:56,851 --> 00:10:58,419
You lazy loafer.

198
00:10:58,519 --> 00:11:00,421
Mr. Gower,
you don't know what you're doing.

199
00:11:00,521 --> 00:11:02,381
You put something wrong
in those capsules.

200
00:11:02,481 --> 00:11:03,716
I know you're unhappy.

201
00:11:03,816 --> 00:11:05,509
You got the telegram, and you're upset.

202
00:11:05,609 --> 00:11:07,428
You put something bad
in those capsules.

203
00:11:07,528 --> 00:11:09,855
It wasn't your fault, Mr. Gower.

204
00:11:10,440 --> 00:11:12,308
Just look and see what you did.

205
00:11:12,408 --> 00:11:14,977
The bottle you took the powder from,
it's poison.

206
00:11:15,077 --> 00:11:16,779
I tell you, it's poison.

207
00:11:16,988 --> 00:11:18,697
I know you feel bad.

208
00:11:23,787 --> 00:11:25,780
- Oh!
- Don't hurt my sore ear again!

209
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:29,908
- Don't hurt my sore ear again.
- Oh, no, no. Oh, George, George.

210
00:11:30,008 --> 00:11:32,827
Oh, Mr. Gower, I won't ever tell anyone.

211
00:11:32,927 --> 00:11:34,287
I know how you're feeling.

212
00:11:34,387 --> 00:11:37,040
I won't ever tell a soul.
Hope to die, I won't.

213
00:11:37,140 --> 00:11:39,008
Oh, George. George.

214
00:11:39,343 --> 00:11:41,920
An overnight bag.
Genuine English cowhide.

215
00:11:42,020 --> 00:11:43,171
Combination lock.

216
00:11:43,271 --> 00:11:46,591
- Fitted up with brushes, combs...
- Nope, nope, nope, nope.

217
00:11:46,691 --> 00:11:48,685
Now, look, Joe. Now, look.

218
00:11:49,186 --> 00:11:51,312
I want a big one.

219
00:11:51,897 --> 00:11:53,139
What did you stop it for?

220
00:11:53,239 --> 00:11:56,476
I want you to take a good look
at that face.

221
00:11:56,576 --> 00:11:57,602
Who is it?

222
00:11:57,702 --> 00:11:58,770
George Bailey.

223
00:11:58,870 --> 00:12:01,815
Oh, you mean the kid that had his ears
slapped back by the druggist?

224
00:12:01,915 --> 00:12:03,199
That's the kid.

225
00:12:05,369 --> 00:12:07,279
It's a good face. I like it.

226
00:12:07,379 --> 00:12:09,205
I like George Bailey.

227
00:12:09,707 --> 00:12:12,284
Tell me,
did he ever tell anyone about the pills?

228
00:12:12,384 --> 00:12:13,543
Not a soul.

229
00:12:13,836 --> 00:12:16,621
Did he ever marry the girl?
Did he ever go exploring?

230
00:12:16,721 --> 00:12:18,464
Well, wait and see.

231
00:12:19,133 --> 00:12:21,293
Big, see? I don't want one for one night.

232
00:12:21,393 --> 00:12:23,378
I want something for 1,001 nights

233
00:12:23,478 --> 00:12:27,966
with plenty of room here for labels
from Italy and Baghdad, Samarkand.

234
00:12:28,066 --> 00:12:29,175
Great big thing, about...

235
00:12:29,275 --> 00:12:31,428
- I see. A flying carpet, huh?
- Yeah.

236
00:12:31,528 --> 00:12:33,930
I don't suppose you'd like
this old secondhand job, would you?

237
00:12:34,030 --> 00:12:35,223
Now you're talking.

238
00:12:35,323 --> 00:12:38,184
Gee whiz, I could use that as a raft
in case the boat sunk.

239
00:12:38,284 --> 00:12:40,528
- How much this cost?
- No charge.

240
00:12:41,196 --> 00:12:43,315
That's my trick ear, Joe.
It sounded like you said "no charge."

241
00:12:43,415 --> 00:12:44,407
That's right.

242
00:12:45,743 --> 00:12:47,277
Well, what's my name doing on it?

243
00:12:47,377 --> 00:12:50,405
A little present from old man Gower.
Came down and picked it out himself.

244
00:12:50,505 --> 00:12:53,867
He did? What do you know about that?
My old boss. Isn't that nice?

245
00:12:53,967 --> 00:12:55,201
What boat are you sailing on?

246
00:12:55,301 --> 00:12:56,828
I'm working across on a cattle boat.

247
00:12:56,928 --> 00:12:59,088
- A cattle boat?
- Okay, I like cows.

248
00:13:01,342 --> 00:13:03,293
Hello, Mr. Gower. How are you?

249
00:13:03,393 --> 00:13:05,837
Thanks ever so much for the baggage.
It's just exactly what I wanted.

250
00:13:05,937 --> 00:13:06,963
Forget it.

251
00:13:07,063 --> 00:13:09,632
- It's wonderful of you to think of me.
- Hope you enjoy it.

252
00:13:09,732 --> 00:13:11,509
I wish I had a million dollars.

253
00:13:11,609 --> 00:13:12,852
Hot dog!

254
00:13:13,562 --> 00:13:15,180
Avast there, Captain Cook!

