Hey, Mary.

498
00:25:36,214 --> 00:25:39,416
As I was lumberin' down the street

499
00:25:39,516 --> 00:25:41,927
Down the street, down the street

500
00:25:42,178 --> 00:25:44,588
Okay, then. I'll throw a rock
at the old Granville house.

501
00:25:44,688 --> 00:25:46,840
Oh, no, don't. I love that old house.

502
00:25:46,940 --> 00:25:48,842
No, you see, you make a wish
and then try and break some glass.

503
00:25:48,942 --> 00:25:50,552
And you got to be
a pretty good shot nowadays, too.

504
00:25:50,652 --> 00:25:53,522
Oh, no, George, don't.
It's full of romance, that old place.

505
00:25:53,898 --> 00:25:55,816
I'd like to live in it.

506
00:25:56,025 --> 00:25:57,017
In that place?

507
00:25:57,117 --> 00:25:59,436
I wouldn't live in it as a ghost.
Now, watch.

508
00:25:59,536 --> 00:26:02,155
Right in the second floor, there. See?

509
00:26:06,869 --> 00:26:08,028
What did you wish, George?

510
00:26:08,128 --> 00:26:10,539
Not just one wish, a whole hatful.

511
00:26:10,706 --> 00:26:12,699
Mary, I know what
I'm gonna do tomorrow

512
00:26:12,799 --> 00:26:15,410
and the next day and next year
and the year after that.

513
00:26:15,510 --> 00:26:18,330
I'm shaking the dust
of this crummy little town off my feet,

514
00:26:18,430 --> 00:26:20,165
and I'm gonna see the world!

515
00:26:20,265 --> 00:26:23,335
Italy, Greece, the Parthenon,
the Coliseum.

516
00:26:23,435 --> 00:26:26,088
Then I'm coming back here and go
to college to see what they know.

517
00:26:26,188 --> 00:26:27,798
And then I'm gonna build things.

518
00:26:27,898 --> 00:26:29,299
I'm gonna build airfields.

519
00:26:29,399 --> 00:26:31,760
I'm gonna build skyscrapers
100 stories high.

520
00:26:31,860 --> 00:26:34,229
I'm gonna build bridges a mile long.

521
00:26:34,605 --> 00:26:36,731
What, are you gonna throw a rock?

522
00:26:40,820 --> 00:26:42,529
Hey, that's pretty good.

523
00:26:43,239 --> 00:26:45,198
What did you wish, Mary?

524
00:26:47,952 --> 00:26:50,154
Buffalo gals
can't you come out tonight?

525
00:26:50,254 --> 00:26:51,488
Can't you come out tonight?

526
00:26:51,588 --> 00:26:53,157
Can't you come out tonight?

527
00:26:53,257 --> 00:26:56,243
Buffalo gals, can't you come out tonight

528
00:26:56,343 --> 00:26:59,329
And

529
00:26:59,429 --> 00:27:03,458
Dance by the light of the moon?

530
00:27:03,558 --> 00:27:05,502
What did you wish
when you threw that rock?

531
00:27:05,602 --> 00:27:07,004
- Oh, no.
- Come on, tell me.

532
00:27:07,104 --> 00:27:08,672
If I told you, it might not come true.

533
00:27:08,772 --> 00:27:10,515
What is it you want, Mary?

534
00:27:10,892 --> 00:27:13,393
What do you want? You want the moon?

535
00:27:13,769 --> 00:27:17,014
Just say the word, and I'll throw a lasso
around it and pull it down.

536
00:27:17,114 --> 00:27:20,901
Hey, that's a pretty good idea.
I'll give you the moon, Mary.

537
00:27:21,068 --> 00:27:22,485
I'll take it.

538
00:27:22,945 --> 00:27:23,987
Then what?

539
00:27:24,447 --> 00:27:27,949
Well, then you could swallow it,
and it would all dissolve, see?

540
00:27:28,409 --> 00:27:31,819
And the moonbeams would shoot out
of your fingers and your toes

541
00:27:31,919 --> 00:27:33,954
and the ends of your hair.

542
00:27:35,290 --> 00:27:38,000
- Am I talking too much?
- Yes!

543
00:27:38,960 --> 00:27:41,287
Why don't you kiss her
instead of talking her to death?

544
00:27:41,387 --> 00:27:42,413
How's that?

545
00:27:42,513 --> 00:27:45,966
Why don't you kiss her
instead of talking her to death?

546
00:27:47,636 --> 00:27:49,212
You want me to kiss her, huh?

547
00:27:49,312 --> 00:27:52,681
Youth is wasted on the wrong people.

548
00:27:53,725 --> 00:27:57,094
Hey. Hey, hold on, hey, mister.
Come on back out here!

549
00:27:57,194 --> 00:28:01,440
I'll show you some kissing that'll put
hair back on your head. What are you...

550
00:28:08,782 --> 00:28:09,865
Mary?

551
00:28:21,002 --> 00:28:23,003
Okay, I give up. Where are you?

552
00:28:23,255 --> 00:28:26,215
Over here in the hydrangea bushes.

553
00:28:26,466 --> 00:28:28,801
Here you are. Catch.

554
00:28:29,970 --> 00:28:32,304
Wait a minute. What am I doing?

555
00:28:36,518 --> 00:28:39,011
This is a very interesting situation.

556
00:28:39,111 --> 00:28:40,938
Please give me my robe.

557
00:28:42,816 --> 00:28:45,518
A man doesn't get in a situation
like this every day.

558
00:28:45,618 --> 00:28:47,603
I'd like to have my robe.

559
00:28:47,703 --> 00:28:49,230
Not in Bedford Falls, anyway.

560
00:28:49,330 --> 00:28:51,532
- Ouch! Oh!
- Gesundheit.

561
00:28:52,492 --> 00:28:54,277
- George Bailey!
- This requires a little thought here.

562
00:28:54,377 --> 00:28:56,028
Give me my robe.

563
00:28:56,128 --> 00:28:58,531
I've read about things like this,
but I've never...

564
00:28:58,631 --> 00:29:01,784
Shame on you!
I'm gonna tell your mother on you.

565
00:29:01,884 --> 00:29:04,453
My mother's way up on the corner there.

566
00:29:04,553 --> 00:29:06,497
I'll call the police.

567
00:29:06,597 --> 00:29:09,375
They're way downtown.
They'd be on my side, too.

568
00:29:09,475 --> 00:29:11,343
Then I'm going to scream!

569
00:29:12,053 --> 00:29:13,846
Maybe I could sell tickets.

570
00:29:14,639 --> 00:29:18,050
Let's see. No, the point is

571
00:29:18,150 --> 00:29:20,853
in order to get this robe... I've got it.

572
00:29:21,146 --> 00:29:22,805
I'll make a deal with you, Mary.

573
00:29:22,905 --> 00:29:25,232
George! George!

574
00:29:27,694 --> 00:29:29,978
George, come on home! Quick!

575
00:29:30,078 --> 00:29:32,488
- Your father's had a stroke.
- What?

576
00:29:32,906 --> 00:29:35,734
- Mary, Mary, I'm sorry. I've got to go.
- Come on, George, let's hurry.

577
00:29:35,834 --> 00:29:36,901
- Did you get a doctor?
- Yes.

578
00:29:37,001 --> 00:29:38,828
Campbell's there now.

579
00:29:49,423 --> 00:29:51,041
I think that's all
we'll need you for, George.

580
00:29:51,141 --> 00:29:54,002
- I know you're anxious to make a train.
- I have a taxi waiting downstairs.

581
00:29:54,102 --> 00:29:56,880
I want the board to know
that George gave up his trip to Europe

582
00:29:56,980 --> 00:29:59,716
to help straighten things out here
these past few months.

583
00:29:59,816 --> 00:30:01,676
Good luck to you at school, George.

584
00:30:01,776 --> 00:30:03,720
- Good luck, George.
- Goodbye, George.

585
00:30:03,820 --> 00:30:06,431
And now we come to the real purpose
of this meeting,

586
00:30:06,531 --> 00:30:09,184
to appoint a successor
to our dear friend Peter Bailey.

587
00:30:09,284 --> 00:30:11,436
Mr. Chairman,
I'd like to get to my real purpose.

588
00:30:11,536 --> 00:30:13,730
- Wait just a minute now.
- Wait for what?

589
00:30:13,830 --> 00:30:17,192
I claim this institution
is not necessary to this town.

590
00:30:17,292 --> 00:30:21,112
Therefore, Mr. Chairman, I make
a motion to dissolve this institution

591
00:30:21,212 --> 00:30:24,491
and turn its assets and liabilities
over to the receiver.

592
00:30:24,591 --> 00:30:26,534
Potter, you dirty, contemptible...
I'll wring his neck.

593
00:30:26,634 --> 00:30:27,619
George, did you hear
what that buzzard...

594
00:30:27,719 --> 00:30:28,745
Mr. Chairman.

595
00:30:28,845 --> 00:30:30,622
It's too soon after Peter Bailey's death

596
00:30:30,722 --> 00:30:33,041
to talk about chloroforming
the Building and Loan.

597
00:30:33,141 --> 00:30:35,543
Peter Bailey died three months ago.

598
00:30:35,643 --> 00:30:37,420
I second Mr. Potter's motion.

599
00:30:37,520 --> 00:30:38,922
Very well. In that case,

600
00:30:39,022 --> 00:30:42,884
I'll ask the two executive officers
to withdraw. But before you go,

601
00:30:42,984 --> 00:30:46,096
I'm sure the whole board wishes
to express its deep sorrow

602
00:30:46,196 --> 00:30:48,390
- at the passing of Peter Bailey.
- Thank you very much.

603
00:30:48,490 --> 00:30:50,392
It was his faith and devotion

604
00:30:50,492 --> 00:30:52,060
that are responsible
for this organization.

605
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:54,062
I'll go further than that.

606
00:30:54,162 --> 00:30:58,566
I'll say that to the public
Peter Bailey was the Building and Loan.

607
00:30:58,666 --> 00:31:00,860
That's fine, Potter, coming from you,

608
00:31:00,960 --> 00:31:02,904
considering that you probably
drove him to his grave.

609
00:31:03,004 --> 00:31:05,824
Peter Bailey was not a businessman.

610
00:31:05,924 --> 00:31:07,367
That's what killed him.

611
00:31:07,467 --> 00:31:10,161
Oh, I don't mean any disrespect to him.
God rest his soul.

612
00:31:10,261 --> 00:31:13,714
He was a man of high ideals, so-called.

613
00:31:14,174 --> 00:31:18,052
But ideals without common sense
can ruin this town.

614
00:31:18,846 --> 00:31:21,631
Now, you take this loan here
to Ernie Bishop,

615
00:31:21,731 --> 00:31:25,051
you know,
that fellow that sits around all day

616
00:31:25,151 --> 00:31:27,929
on his brains in his taxi, you know.

617
00:31:28,029 --> 00:31:31,807
I happen to know
the bank turned down this loan.

618
00:31:31,907 --> 00:31:33,600
But he comes here,

619
00:31:33,700 --> 00:31:38,447
and we're building him
a house worth $5,000.

620
00:31:39,198 --> 00:31:41,608
- Why?
- Well, I handled that, Mr. Potter.

621
00:31:41,708 --> 00:31:44,570
You have all the papers there.
His salary, insurance.

622
00:31:44,670 --> 00:31:45,988
I can personally vouch for his character.

623
00:31:46,088 --> 00:31:47,998
- A friend of yours?
- Yes, sir.

624
00:31:48,541 --> 00:31:52,327
You see, if you shoot pool
with some employee here,

625
00:31:52,427 --> 00:31:54,671
you can come and borrow money.

626
00:31:54,922 --> 00:31:56,832
What does that get us?

627
00:31:56,932 --> 00:31:59,793
A discontented, lazy rabble

628
00:31:59,893 --> 00:32:01,795
instead of a thrifty working class.

629
00:32:01,895 --> 00:32:05,674
And all because
a few starry-eyed dreamers

630
00:32:05,774 --> 00:32:08,969
like Peter Bailey stir them up
and fill their heads

631
00:32:09,069 --> 00:32:11,305
with a lot of impossible ideas.

632
00:32:11,405 --> 00:32:13,182
Now, I say...

633
00:32:13,282 --> 00:32:16,143
Just a minute. Just a minute.
Now, hold on, Mr. Potter.

634
00:32:16,243 --> 00:32:19,480
You're right when you say my father
was no businessman. I know that.

635
00:32:19,580 --> 00:32:22,191
Why he ever started this cheap
penny-ante Building and Loan

636
00:32:22,291 --> 00:32:23,358
I'll never know.

637
00:32:23,458 --> 00:32:26,320
But neither you nor anybody else
can say anything against his character,

638
00:32:26,420 --> 00:32:28,113
because his whole life was...

639
00:32:28,213 --> 00:32:30,824
Why, in the 25 years since he
and Uncle Billy started this thing,

640
00:32:30,924 --> 00:32:33,202
he never once thought of himself.
Isn't that right, Uncle Billy?

641
00:32:33,302 --> 00:32:36,163
He didn't save enough money
to send Harry to school, let alone me.

642
00:32:36,263 --> 00:32:38,999
But he did help a few people
get out of your slums, Mr. Potter.

643
00:32:39,099 --> 00:32:43,170
And what's wrong with that?
Why, here, you're all businessmen here.

644
00:32:43,270 --> 00:32:46,507
Don't it make them better citizens, and
doesn't it make them better customers?

645
00:32:46,607 --> 00:32:48,800
You said that they...
What'd you say just a minute ago?

646
00:32:48,900 --> 00:32:50,677
They had to wait and save their money

647
00:32:50,777 --> 00:32:52,221
before they even thought
of a decent home.

648
00:32:52,321 --> 00:32:54,014
Wait? Wait for what?

649
00:32:54,114 --> 00:32:55,766
Until their children grow up
and leave them?

650
00:32:55,866 --> 00:32:58,018
Until they're so old
and broken-down that they...

651
00:32:58,118 --> 00:33:00,729
Do you know how long it takes
a working man to save $5,000?

652
00:33:00,829 --> 00:33:04,191
Just remember this, Mr. Potter,
that this rabble you're talking about,

653
00:33:04,291 --> 00:33:08,195
they do most of the working and paying
and living and dying in this community.

654
00:33:08,295 --> 00:33:10,739
Well, is it too much to have them work
and pay and live and die

655
00:33:10,839 --> 00:33:12,616
in a couple of decent rooms and a bath?

656
00:33:12,716 --> 00:33:14,793
Anyway, my father didn't think so.

657
00:33:15,461 --> 00:33:17,746
People were human beings to him,
but to you,

658
00:33:17,846 --> 00:33:20,799
a warped, frustrated old man,
they're cattle.

659
00:33:20,925 --> 00:33:23,377
Well, in my book, he died
a much richer man than you'll ever be.

660
00:33:23,477 --> 00:33:25,379
I'm not interested in your book.

661
00:33:25,479 --> 00:33:28,215
I'm talking about the Building and Loan.

662
00:33:28,315 --> 00:33:30,008
I know very well
what you're talking about.

663
00:33:30,108 --> 00:33:32,385
You're talking about something
you can't get your fingers on,

664
00:33:32,485 --> 00:33:35,304
and it's galling you.
That's what you're talking about, I know.

665
00:33:35,404 --> 00:33:37,690
Well, I've said too much. I...

666
00:33:38,149 --> 00:33:41,060
You're the Board here.
You do what you want with this thing.

667
00:33:41,160 --> 00:33:42,728
There's just one thing more, though.

668
00:33:42,828 --> 00:33:45,439
This town needs
this measly one-horse institution

669
00:33:45,539 --> 00:33:49,110
if only to have someplace where people
can come without crawling to Potter.

670
00:33:49,210 --> 00:33:50,327
Come on, Uncle Billy.

671
00:33:56,376 --> 00:33:59,712
Sentimental hogwash. I want my motion.

672
00:34:01,840 --> 00:34:04,417
Boy, oh boy, that was telling him,
George, old boy.

673
00:34:04,517 --> 00:34:06,294
You shut his big mouth.
You should have heard him.

674
00:34:06,394 --> 00:34:08,087
What happened?
We heard a lot of yelling.

675
00:34:08,187 --> 00:34:10,798
Well, we're being voted
out of business after 25 years.

676
00:34:10,898 --> 00:34:14,385
- Easy come, easy go.
- Here it is. "Help wanted. Female."

677
00:34:14,485 --> 00:34:16,429
You still want me
to hang around, George?

678
00:34:16,529 --> 00:34:19,056
- Yeah, I'll be right down.
- Yeah, hey, you'll miss your train.

679
00:34:19,156 --> 00:34:20,933
You're a week late for school already.
Go on.

680
00:34:21,033 --> 00:34:23,811
- What's going on in there?
- Never mind. Don't worry about that.

681
00:34:23,911 --> 00:34:26,939
They're putting us out of business.
So what? I can get another job.

682
00:34:27,039 --> 00:34:28,774
- I'm only 55.
- 56.

683
00:34:28,874 --> 00:34:31,193
Go on, go on.
Hey, look, you gave up your boat trip,

684
00:34:31,293 --> 00:34:32,862
now you don't want to miss college,
too, do you?

685
00:34:32,962 --> 00:34:35,406
George! George!
They voted Potter down.

686
00:34:35,506 --> 00:34:37,291
They want to keep it going.

687
00:34:38,293 --> 00:34:39,827
You did it, George. You did it.

688
00:34:39,927 --> 00:34:42,121
They got one condition,
only one condition.

689
00:34:42,221 --> 00:34:43,789
- What's that?
- And that's the best part of it.

690
00:34:43,889 --> 00:34:45,875
They've appointed George here
as Executive Secretary

691
00:34:45,975 --> 00:34:47,251
to take his father's place.

692
00:34:47,351 --> 00:34:50,171
- Oh, no! But, Uncle Billy...
- You can keep him on. That's all right.

693
00:34:50,271 --> 00:34:52,173
As Secretary,
you can hire anyone you like.

694
00:34:52,273 --> 00:34:54,884
Dr. Campbell, now let's get
this thing straight. I'm leaving.

695
00:34:54,984 --> 00:34:56,594
I'm leaving right now.
I'm going to school.

696
00:34:56,694 --> 00:34:59,138
This is my last chance.
Uncle Billy here, he's your man.

697
00:34:59,238 --> 00:35:02,066
But, George,
they'll vote with Potter otherwise.

698
00:35:03,902 --> 00:35:06,904
- I know, I know, he didn't go.
- That's right.

699
00:35:07,238 --> 00:35:10,316
Not only that, but he gave
his school money to his brother, Harry,

700
00:35:10,416 --> 00:35:11,901
and sent him to college.

701
00:35:12,001 --> 00:35:13,861
Harry became a football star.

702
00:35:13,961 --> 00:35:15,245
Made second team all-American.

703
00:35:15,664 --> 00:35:17,948
Yeah, but what happened to George?

704
00:35:18,048 --> 00:35:21,243
George got four years older,
waiting for Harry to come back

705
00:35:21,343 --> 00:35:23,412
and take over the Building and Loans.

706
00:35:23,512 --> 00:35:25,831
There are plenty of jobs around
for somebody that likes to travel.

707
00:35:25,931 --> 00:35:26,916
Look at this. Here.

708
00:35:27,016 --> 00:35:31,336
Venezuela oil fields. "Wanted,
man with construction experience."

709
00:35:31,436 --> 00:35:33,421
Here's the Yukon, right here.

710
00:35:33,521 --> 00:35:35,890
"Wanted,
man with engineering experience."

711
00:35:37,017 --> 00:35:38,843
There she blows.

712
00:35:38,943 --> 00:35:41,805
You know what the three most exciting
sounds in the world are?

713
00:35:41,905 --> 00:35:44,140
Breakfast is served.
Lunch is served. Dinner...

714
00:35:44,240 --> 00:35:47,936
No, no, no, no! Anchor chains,
plane motors and train whistles.

715
00:35:48,036 --> 00:35:50,188
- Peanut?
- There's the professor now.

716
00:35:50,288 --> 00:35:52,565
Old Professor Phi Beta Kappa
all-American Bailey.

717
00:35:52,665 --> 00:35:54,693
Why, old George
"Geographic Explorer" Bailey.

718
00:35:54,793 --> 00:35:57,362
What? No husky dogs? No sled?
Uncle Billy, you haven't changed a bit.

719
00:35:57,462 --> 00:35:58,988
Nobody ever changes here,
you know that.

720
00:35:59,088 --> 00:36:00,740
Oh, am I glad to see you.

721
00:36:00,840 --> 00:36:03,034
- Say, where's Mother?
- She's home, cooking the fatted calf.

722
00:36:03,134 --> 00:36:04,953
- Come on, let's go.
- Oh, wait! Wait, wait a minute.

723
00:36:05,053 --> 00:36:07,997
George, Uncle Billy,
I want you to meet Ruth.

724
00:36:08,097 --> 00:36:09,416
- Hello.
- How do you do?

725
00:36:09,516 --> 00:36:12,252
- Ruth Dakin.
- Ruth Dakin Bailey, if you don't mind.

726
00:36:12,352 --> 00:36:14,713
- Huh?
- Well, I wired you I had a surprise.

727
00:36:14,813 --> 00:36:16,423
Here she is. Meet the wife.

728
00:36:16,523 --> 00:36:19,350
Well, what do you know? A wife.

729
00:36:20,144 --> 00:36:23,229
- Well, how do you do? Congratulations.
- How do you do?

730
00:36:23,564 --> 00:36:26,015
What am I doing? Congratulations!

731
00:36:26,115 --> 00:36:27,851
- Doggone it, Harry, you...
- They're married!

732
