Annie, we're just two old maids now.

973
00:51:00,148 --> 00:51:02,267
You speak for yourself, Miss B.

974
00:51:04,895 --> 00:51:08,315
If either of you two
see a stranger around here, it's me.

975
00:51:10,526 --> 00:51:12,936
Hey, look.
There's somebody driving this cab.

976
00:51:13,036 --> 00:51:14,855
Bert the cop sent this over.

977
00:51:14,955 --> 00:51:17,316
He said to float away
to Happyland on the bubbles.

978
00:51:17,416 --> 00:51:19,610
Oh, look at this. Old Bert. Champagne!

979
00:51:19,710 --> 00:51:22,863
By the way, where are you two going
on this here now honeymoon?

980
00:51:22,963 --> 00:51:25,073
Where are we going? Look at this.

981
00:51:25,173 --> 00:51:27,534
There's the kitty, Ernie.
Here, come on, count it, Mary.

982
00:51:27,634 --> 00:51:29,703
I feel like a bootlegger's wife. Look.

983
00:51:29,803 --> 00:51:32,164
You know what we're gonna do?
We're gonna shoot the works.

984
00:51:32,264 --> 00:51:34,498
A whole week in New York.
A whole week in Bermuda.

985
00:51:34,598 --> 00:51:37,043
The highest hotels,
the oldest champagne,

986
00:51:37,143 --> 00:51:41,631
the richest caviar, the hottest music
and the prettiest wife.

987
00:51:41,731 --> 00:51:43,966
That does it! Then what?

988
00:51:44,066 --> 00:51:47,061
- Then what, honey?
- After that, who cares?

989
00:51:47,562 --> 00:51:49,521
That does it, come here. Come here.

990
00:51:52,692 --> 00:51:54,226
Don't look now,
but there's something funny

991
00:51:54,326 --> 00:51:56,520
going on over there
at the bank, George.

992
00:51:56,620 --> 00:52:00,658
I've never really seen one, but that's got
all the earmarks of being a run.

993
00:52:08,166 --> 00:52:11,160
Hey, Ernie, if you got any money
in the bank, you better hurry.

994
00:52:11,260 --> 00:52:12,995
George, let's not stop. Let's go!

995
00:52:13,095 --> 00:52:14,588
Just a minute, dear.

996
00:52:17,592 --> 00:52:21,178
- Please, let's not stop, George.
- I'll be back in a minute, Mary.

997
00:52:37,737 --> 00:52:40,231
Well, hello, everybody.
Mrs. Thompson, how are you?

998
00:52:40,331 --> 00:52:43,158
Charlie? What's the matter here,
can't you get in?

999
00:53:00,468 --> 00:53:02,761
What is this, Uncle Billy? A holiday?

1000
00:53:03,012 --> 00:53:04,179
George.

1001
00:53:04,889 --> 00:53:08,892
Come on in, everybody.
That's right. Just come on in.

1002
00:53:09,144 --> 00:53:10,394
Look out, you.

1003
00:53:12,605 --> 00:53:14,223
Now, look, why don't you all sit down?

1004
00:53:14,323 --> 00:53:16,483
There are a lot of seats over there.

1005
00:53:17,485 --> 00:53:19,361
Just make yourselves at home.

1006
00:53:20,947 --> 00:53:23,365
George, can I see you a minute?

1007
00:53:23,950 --> 00:53:26,193
- Why didn't you call me?
- I just did, but they said you left.

1008
00:53:26,293 --> 00:53:27,862
This is a pickle, George.
This is a pickle.

1009
00:53:27,962 --> 00:53:29,488
All right, now, what happened?
How did it start?

1010
00:53:29,588 --> 00:53:30,698
How does a thing like this ever start?

1011
00:53:30,798 --> 00:53:32,450
- All I know is the bank called our loan.
- When?

1012
00:53:32,550 --> 00:53:34,743
About an hour ago.
I handed over all our cash.

1013
00:53:34,843 --> 00:53:36,161
- All of it?
- Every cent of it,

1014
00:53:36,261 --> 00:53:38,621
- and still it was less than we owe them.
- Holy mackerel!

1015
00:53:38,721 --> 00:53:40,832
And then I got scared, George,
and closed the doors.

1016
00:53:40,932 --> 00:53:42,592
I... I...

1017
00:53:44,636 --> 00:53:46,379
The whole town's gone crazy.

1018
00:53:46,479 --> 00:53:47,805
Yeah, hello?

1019
00:53:47,973 --> 00:53:50,016
George, it's Potter.

1020
00:53:53,562 --> 00:53:54,637
Hello?

1021
00:53:54,737 --> 00:53:59,100
George, there is a rumor around town
that you've closed your doors.

1022
00:53:59,200 --> 00:54:00,651
Is that true?

1023
00:54:01,028 --> 00:54:03,271
Oh, well, I'm very glad to hear that.

1024
00:54:03,371 --> 00:54:06,691
George, are you all right?
Do you need any police?

1025
00:54:06,791 --> 00:54:08,159
Police? What for?

1026
00:54:08,368 --> 00:54:12,205
Well, mobs get pretty ugly
sometimes, you know.

1027
00:54:12,498 --> 00:54:17,001
George, I'm going all out
to help in this crisis.

1028
00:54:17,294 --> 00:54:22,256
I've just guaranteed the bank
sufficient funds to meet their needs.

1029
00:54:22,591 --> 00:54:25,968
They'll close up for a week
and then reopen.

1030
00:54:26,845 --> 00:54:28,638
He just took over the bank.

1031
00:54:28,889 --> 00:54:30,507
I may lose a fortune,

1032
00:54:30,607 --> 00:54:34,469
but I'm willing
to guarantee your people, too.

1033
00:54:34,569 --> 00:54:37,013
Just tell them
to bring their shares over here,

1034
00:54:37,113 --> 00:54:39,682
and I will pay 50 cents on the dollar.

1035
00:54:39,782 --> 00:54:41,893
You never miss a trick, do you, Potter?

1036
00:54:41,993 --> 00:54:43,144
Well, you're gonna miss this one.

1037
00:54:43,244 --> 00:54:46,948
If you close your doors before 6:00 p.m.,
you will never reopen.

1038
00:54:55,749 --> 00:54:57,200
George, was it a nice wedding?

1039
00:54:57,300 --> 00:54:59,293
Gosh, I wanted to be there.

1040
00:54:59,711 --> 00:55:00,753
Yeah.

1041
00:55:02,673 --> 00:55:04,590
You can take this one off now.

1042
00:55:13,433 --> 00:55:18,771
Now, just remember that this thing
isn't as black as it appeared.

1043
00:55:28,532 --> 00:55:30,358
I have some news for you, folks.

1044
00:55:30,458 --> 00:55:31,860
I was just talking to old man Potter,

1045
00:55:31,960 --> 00:55:33,570
and he's guaranteed cash payments
at the bank.

1046
00:55:33,670 --> 00:55:35,195
The bank's gonna reopen next week.

1047
00:55:35,295 --> 00:55:37,197
But, George, I got my money here.

1048
00:55:37,297 --> 00:55:38,866
Did he guarantee this place?

1049
00:55:38,966 --> 00:55:41,994
Well, no, Charlie. I didn't even ask him.
We don't need Potter over here.

1050
00:55:42,094 --> 00:55:43,795
Then, I'll take mine now.

1051
00:55:44,213 --> 00:55:45,797
No, but you're...

1052
00:55:46,632 --> 00:55:48,709
You're thinking of this place all wrong,

1053
00:55:48,809 --> 00:55:52,379
as if I had the money back in a safe.
The money's not here.

1054
00:55:52,479 --> 00:55:55,007
Well, your money's in Joe's house.
That's right next to yours.

1055
00:55:55,107 --> 00:55:57,342
And in the Kennedy house
and Mrs. Macklin's house

1056
00:55:57,442 --> 00:55:58,927
and 100 others.

1057
00:55:59,027 --> 00:56:00,596
Why, you're lending them
the money to build,

1058
00:56:00,696 --> 00:56:02,723
and then, they're gonna pay it back
to you as best they can.

1059
00:56:02,823 --> 00:56:04,474
Now, what are you gonna do,
foreclose on them?

1060
00:56:04,574 --> 00:56:10,614
I got $242 in here,
and $242 isn't going to break anybody.

1061
00:56:11,490 --> 00:56:14,075
Okay, Tom. All right.

1062
00:56:14,327 --> 00:56:16,904
Here you are. You sign this.
You'll get your money in 60 days.

1063
00:56:17,004 --> 00:56:18,113
Sixty days?

1064
00:56:18,213 --> 00:56:20,240
Now, that's what you agreed to
when you bought your shares.

1065
00:56:20,340 --> 00:56:22,451
- Tom! Tom, did you get your money?
- No.

1066
00:56:22,551 --> 00:56:23,577
Well, I did.

1067
00:56:23,677 --> 00:56:26,288
Old man Potter'll pay 50 cents
on the dollar for every share you've got.

1068
00:56:26,388 --> 00:56:28,957
- Fifty cents on the dollar!
- Yes, cash!

1069
00:56:29,057 --> 00:56:30,626
Well, what do you say?

1070
00:56:30,726 --> 00:56:33,337
Now, Tom, you have to stick
to your original agreement.

1071
00:56:33,437 --> 00:56:34,755
Now, give us 60 days on this.

1072
00:56:34,855 --> 00:56:36,924
- Okay, Randall.
- Are you going to go to Potter's?

1073
00:56:37,024 --> 00:56:39,092
Better to get half than nothing.

1074
00:56:39,192 --> 00:56:41,269
Tom! Tom!

1075
00:56:41,687 --> 00:56:43,521
Randall! Now, Randall, wait! Wait.

1076
00:56:43,898 --> 00:56:47,684
Now, listen. Now, listen to me.
I beg of you not to do this thing.

1077
00:56:47,784 --> 00:56:49,853
If Potter gets a hold
of this Building and Loan,

1078
00:56:49,953 --> 00:56:51,897
there'll never be
another decent house built in this town.

1079
00:56:51,997 --> 00:56:53,482
He's already got charge of the bank.

1080
00:56:53,582 --> 00:56:55,609
He's got the bus line.
He got the department stores.

1081
00:56:55,709 --> 00:56:58,445
And now he's after us. Why?
Well, it's very simple.

1082
00:56:58,545 --> 00:57:00,781
Because we're cutting in
on his business, that's why.

1083
00:57:00,881 --> 00:57:02,950
And because he wants
to keep you living in his slums

1084
00:57:03,050 --> 00:57:04,952
and paying the kind of rent he decides.

1085
00:57:05,052 --> 00:57:06,954
Joe, you had one
of those Potter houses, didn't you?

1086
00:57:07,054 --> 00:57:08,038
Well, have you forgotten?

1087
00:57:08,138 --> 00:57:10,499
Have you forgotten what he charged you
for that broken-down shack?

1088
00:57:10,599 --> 00:57:13,710
Here, Ed, you know. You remember last
year when things weren't going so well

1089
00:57:13,810 --> 00:57:14,962
and you couldn't make your payments.

1090
00:57:15,062 --> 00:57:16,505
Well, you didn't lose your house,
did you?

1091
00:57:16,605 --> 00:57:18,340
You think Potter would've
let you keep it?

1092
00:57:18,440 --> 00:57:21,134
Can't you understand
what's happening here?

1093
00:57:21,234 --> 00:57:22,803
Don't you see what's happening?

1094
00:57:22,903 --> 00:57:25,597
Potter isn't selling.
Potter's buying, and why?

1095
00:57:25,697 --> 00:57:27,849
Because we're panicky and he's not.
That's why.

1096
00:57:27,949 --> 00:57:29,142
He's picking up some bargain.

1097
00:57:29,242 --> 00:57:31,603
Now we can get through
this thing all right.

1098
00:57:31,703 --> 00:57:33,480
We've got to stick together, though.

1099
00:57:33,580 --> 00:57:35,064
We've got to have faith in each other.

1100
00:57:35,164 --> 00:57:38,359
But my husband hasn't worked
in over a year, and I need money.

1101
00:57:38,459 --> 00:57:40,152
How am going to live
until the bank opens?

1102
00:57:40,252 --> 00:57:42,571
- I got doctor bills to pay.
- I need cash.

1103
00:57:42,671 --> 00:57:44,573
I can't feed my kids on faith.

1104
00:57:44,673 --> 00:57:46,325
How much do you need?

1105
00:57:46,425 --> 00:57:49,920
Hey! I got $2,000.

1106
00:57:50,547 --> 00:57:52,999
Here's $2,000.
This'll tide us over till the bank reopens.

1107
00:57:53,099 --> 00:57:55,876
- All right, Tom, how much do you need?
- $242.

1108
00:57:55,976 --> 00:57:58,504
Tom, just enough to tide you over
until the bank reopens.

1109
00:57:58,604 --> 00:58:00,764
I'll take $242.

1110
00:58:03,560 --> 00:58:05,344
- There you are.
- That'll close my account.

1111
00:58:05,444 --> 00:58:07,722
Your account's still here. That's a loan.

1112
00:58:07,822 --> 00:58:11,183
- Okay. All right, Ed?
- I got $300 here, George.

1113
00:58:11,283 --> 00:58:14,854
Now, Ed, what'll it take
till the bank opens? What do you need?

1114
00:58:14,954 --> 00:58:17,273
Well, I suppose $20.

1115
00:58:17,373 --> 00:58:20,192
$20. Now you're talking.
Thanks, Ed. That's fine.

1116
00:58:20,292 --> 00:58:21,861
All right, now, Mrs. Thompson,
how much do you want?

1117
00:58:21,961 --> 00:58:23,237
But it's your own money, George.

1118
00:58:23,337 --> 00:58:25,031
Never mind about that.
How much do you want?

1119
00:58:25,131 --> 00:58:27,199
- I can get along with $20, all right.
- $20, fine.

1120
00:58:27,299 --> 00:58:29,410
- And I'll sign the paper.
- You don't have to sign anything.

1121
00:58:29,510 --> 00:58:31,620
I know you. You pay it when you can.
That's okay.

1122
00:58:31,720 --> 00:58:35,132
