01:04:21,726 --> 01:04:25,396
- Sit down, there.
- Here, now, get the dog, now. That's it.

1203
01:04:26,606 --> 01:04:28,816
- Goat, too.
- Everybody!

1204
01:04:29,109 --> 01:04:30,484
All in!

1205
01:04:32,654 --> 01:04:34,571
Bye-bye! Bye-bye!

1206
01:04:37,242 --> 01:04:38,367
All in?

1207
01:04:57,345 --> 01:04:59,805
Mr. and Mrs. Martini, welcome home.

1208
01:05:00,306 --> 01:05:02,850
Good old George,
he's always making a speech.

1209
01:05:03,893 --> 01:05:05,227
Hee-haw!

1210
01:05:05,437 --> 01:05:09,064
- Sam Wainwright.
- Oh, who cares.

1211
01:05:09,607 --> 01:05:12,776
Bread. That this house
may never know hunger.

1212
01:05:13,528 --> 01:05:16,864
Salt. That life may always have flavor.

1213
01:05:17,282 --> 01:05:20,734
And wine. That joy and prosperity
may reign forever.

1214
01:05:20,834 --> 01:05:22,578
Enter the Martini castle.

1215
01:05:24,414 --> 01:05:26,866
Look, Mr. Potter,
it's no skin off my nose.

1216
01:05:26,966 --> 01:05:28,784
I'm just your little rent collector.

1217
01:05:28,884 --> 01:05:31,662
But you can't laugh off
this Bailey Park anymore.

1218
01:05:31,762 --> 01:05:32,880
Look at it.

1219
01:05:33,756 --> 01:05:35,791
Congressman Black is here
to see you, sir.

1220
01:05:35,891 --> 01:05:38,835
Oh, tell the Congressman to wait.
Go on.

1221
01:05:38,935 --> 01:05:41,713
Fifteen years ago, a half a dozen
houses stuck here and there.

1222
01:05:41,813 --> 01:05:44,048
There's the old cemetery, squirrels,
buttercups, daisies.

1223
01:05:44,148 --> 01:05:46,350
I used to hunt rabbits there myself.

1224
01:05:47,227 --> 01:05:48,561
Look at it today.

1225
01:05:48,687 --> 01:05:51,522
Dozens of the prettiest little homes
you ever saw,

1226
01:05:51,690 --> 01:05:54,893
90% owned by suckers
who used to pay rent to you.

1227
01:05:54,993 --> 01:05:58,313
Your Potter's Field, my dear
Mr. Employer, is becoming just that.

1228
01:05:58,413 --> 01:06:01,816
And are the local yokels making with
those David and Goliath wisecracks.

1229
01:06:01,916 --> 01:06:03,651
Oh, they are, are they?

1230
01:06:03,751 --> 01:06:06,654
Even though they know
the Baileys never made a dime out of it.

1231
01:06:06,754 --> 01:06:09,240
You know very well why.
The Baileys were all chumps.

1232
01:06:09,340 --> 01:06:11,284
Every one of these homes is worth

1233
01:06:11,384 --> 01:06:13,495
twice what it cost
the Building and Loan to build.

1234
01:06:13,595 --> 01:06:15,997
- If I were you, Mr. Potter...
- You are not me.

1235
01:06:16,097 --> 01:06:19,592
As I say, it's no skin off my nose,

1236
01:06:22,721 --> 01:06:24,672
but one of these days
this bright young man

1237
01:06:24,772 --> 01:06:27,391
is gonna be asking
George Bailey for a job.

1238
01:06:29,770 --> 01:06:32,889
The Bailey family has been
a boil on my neck long enough.

1239
01:06:32,989 --> 01:06:35,107
- Yes, sir?
- Come in here.

1240
01:06:35,442 --> 01:06:37,602
We just stopped in town
to take a look at the new factory,

1241
01:06:37,702 --> 01:06:39,687
and then we're gonna
drive on down to Florida.

1242
01:06:39,787 --> 01:06:41,397
Why don't you
have your friends join us?

1243
01:06:41,497 --> 01:06:44,909
Why, sure. Hey, why don't you kids
drive down with us, huh?

1244
01:06:45,285 --> 01:06:48,029
Oh, I'm afraid I couldn't get away, Sam.

1245
01:06:48,129 --> 01:06:50,198
Still got the nose
to the old grindstone, eh?

1246
01:06:50,298 --> 01:06:53,868
Jane, I offered to let George in
on the ground floor in plastics,

1247
01:06:53,968 --> 01:06:55,119
and he turned me down cold.

1248
01:06:55,219 --> 01:06:57,997
- Oh, now, don't rub it in.
- I'm not rubbing it in.

1249
01:06:58,097 --> 01:06:59,707
Well, I guess we better run along.

1250
01:06:59,807 --> 01:07:01,834
- Awfully happy to have met you, Mary.
- Nice meeting you, too.

1251
01:07:01,934 --> 01:07:03,294
- Goodbye. Glad to see you.
- Goodbye, George.

1252
01:07:03,394 --> 01:07:04,837
So long, George.
See you in the funny papers.

1253
01:07:04,937 --> 01:07:07,006
- So long, Mary.
- Bye, Sam. Have fun.

1254
01:07:07,106 --> 01:07:09,092
- Thanks for dropping around.
- Florida!

1255
01:07:09,192 --> 01:07:10,893
- Hee-haw!
- Hee-haw.

1256
01:07:40,172 --> 01:07:41,506
Thank you, sir.

1257
01:07:42,049 --> 01:07:44,042
- That's quite a cigar, Mr. Potter.
- You like it?

1258
01:07:44,142 --> 01:07:45,677
I'll send you a box.

1259
01:07:54,520 --> 01:07:55,812
Well, I...

1260
01:07:57,356 --> 01:07:58,849
I suppose I'll find out sooner or later,

1261
01:07:58,949 --> 01:08:01,818
but just what exactly
did you want to see me about?

1262
01:08:03,904 --> 01:08:07,532
George, now that's just what I like
so much about you.

1263
01:08:08,034 --> 01:08:11,653
George, I am an old man,
and most people hate me.

1264
01:08:11,753 --> 01:08:14,740
But I don't like them, either,
so that makes it all even.

1265
01:08:14,840 --> 01:08:16,992
You know just as well as I do

1266
01:08:17,092 --> 01:08:19,620
that I run practically everything
in this town

1267
01:08:19,720 --> 01:08:22,297
but the Bailey Building and Loan.

1268
01:08:22,757 --> 01:08:26,835
You know, also, that for a number of
years I've been trying to get control of it.

1269
01:08:26,935 --> 01:08:29,554
Or kill it. But I haven't been able to do it.

1270
01:08:29,764 --> 01:08:31,723
You have been stopping me.

1271
01:08:32,850 --> 01:08:35,969
In fact, you have beaten me, George,

1272
01:08:36,069 --> 01:08:40,565
and as anyone in this county
can tell you, that takes some doing.

1273
01:08:41,651 --> 01:08:44,353
Take during the Depression,
for instance.

1274
01:08:44,453 --> 01:08:47,522
You and I were the only ones
that kept our heads.

1275
01:08:47,622 --> 01:08:51,568
You saved the Building and Loan.
I saved all the rest.

1276
01:08:51,668 --> 01:08:54,321
Yes. Well, most people say
you stole all the rest.

1277
01:08:54,421 --> 01:08:57,707
The envious ones say that,
George, the suckers.

1278
01:08:58,668 --> 01:09:02,754
Now, I have stated my side very frankly.

1279
01:09:03,089 --> 01:09:05,256
Now let's look at your side.

1280
01:09:06,175 --> 01:09:13,098
Young man, 27-28, married,
making, say, $40 a week.

1281
01:09:13,224 --> 01:09:15,133
- $45.
- $45.

1282
01:09:15,233 --> 01:09:16,351
$45.

1283
01:09:16,727 --> 01:09:20,597
Out of which, after supporting
your mother and paying your bills,

1284
01:09:20,697 --> 01:09:23,775
you're able to keep, say, $10,
if you skimp.

1285
01:09:23,901 --> 01:09:28,188
A child or two comes along, and you
won't even be able to save the $10.

1286
01:09:28,288 --> 01:09:33,819
Now, if this young man of 28
was a common, ordinary yokel,

1287
01:09:33,919 --> 01:09:35,487
I'd say he was doing fine.

1288
01:09:35,587 --> 01:09:39,865
But George Bailey is not a common,
ordinary yokel.

1289
01:09:39,965 --> 01:09:43,619
He is an intelligent, smart,
ambitious young man,

1290
01:09:43,719 --> 01:09:46,914
who hates his job,
who hates the Building and Loan

1291
01:09:47,014 --> 01:09:48,674
almost as much as I do.

1292
01:09:49,384 --> 01:09:53,971
A young man who's been dying to get
out on his own ever since he was born.

1293
01:09:54,389 --> 01:09:57,216
A young man... The smartest one
of the crowd, mind you.

1294
01:09:57,316 --> 01:09:58,884
A young man who has to sit by

1295
01:09:58,984 --> 01:10:02,430
and watch his friends go places
because he's trapped.

1296
01:10:02,530 --> 01:10:06,183
Yes, sir,
trapped into frittering his life away,

1297
01:10:06,283 --> 01:10:08,861
playing nursemaid
to a lot of garlic eaters.

1298
01:10:10,321 --> 01:10:13,657
Do I paint a correct picture,
or do I exaggerate?

1299
01:10:16,119 --> 01:10:18,654
- Now, what's your point, Mr. Potter?
- My point?

1300
01:10:18,754 --> 01:10:21,323
- My point is I want to hire you.
- Hire me?

1301
01:10:21,423 --> 01:10:24,668
Yeah, I want you to manage my affairs,
run my properties.

1302
01:10:24,919 --> 01:10:30,007
George, I'll start you out
at $20,000 a year.

1303
01:10:33,845 --> 01:10:36,797
$20,000 a year?

1304
01:10:36,897 --> 01:10:40,259
You wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town,

1305
01:10:40,359 --> 01:10:43,053
buying your wife a lot of fine clothes,

1306
01:10:43,153 --> 01:10:45,931
a couple of business trips
to New York a year,

1307
01:10:46,031 --> 01:10:47,850
maybe once in a while Europe.

1308
01:10:47,950 --> 01:10:49,268
You wouldn't mind that,
would you, George?

1309
01:10:49,368 --> 01:10:50,694
Would I?

1310
01:10:53,698 --> 01:10:56,025
You're not talking to somebody else
around here, are you?

1311
01:10:56,125 --> 01:10:57,818
You know, this is me.
You remember me?

1312
01:10:57,918 --> 01:10:59,695
- George Bailey.
- George Bailey.

1313
01:10:59,795 --> 01:11:02,873
Yeah, George Bailey,
whose ship has just come in.

1314
01:11:04,167 --> 01:11:07,377
Provided he has enough brains
to climb aboard.

1315
01:11:15,720 --> 01:11:17,137
Holy mackerel.

1316
01:11:20,225 --> 01:11:22,760
Well, how about the Building and Loan?

1317
01:11:22,860 --> 01:11:26,271
Oh, confound it, man,
are you afraid of success?

1318
01:11:26,397 --> 01:11:31,310
I'm offering you a three-years contract
at $20,000 a year, starting today.

1319
01:11:31,410 --> 01:11:33,111
Is it a deal, or isn't it?

1320
01:11:34,739 --> 01:11:36,406
Well, Mr. Potter, I...

1321
01:11:36,616 --> 01:11:40,409
I know I ought to jump
at the chance but I... I just...

1322
01:11:41,537 --> 01:11:45,573
I wonder if it would be possible for you
to give me 24 hours to think it over?

1323
01:11:45,673 --> 01:11:47,325
Sure, sure, sure.

1324
01:11:47,425 --> 01:11:49,994
You go on home
and talk about it to your wife.

1325
01:11:50,094 --> 01:11:51,621
I'd like to do that.

1326
01:11:51,721 --> 01:11:54,040
Yeah. In the meantime,
I'll draw up the papers.

1327
01:11:54,140 --> 01:11:56,050
- All right, sir.
- Okay, George?

1328
01:11:57,553 --> 01:11:59,095
Okay, Mr. Potter.

1329
01:12:07,271 --> 01:12:11,566
No. No. No, no,
now wait a minute, here.

1330
01:12:12,442 --> 01:12:15,270
I don't need 24 hours.
I don't have to talk to anybody.

1331
01:12:15,370 --> 01:12:19,107
I know right now, and the answer is no.
No, doggone it!

1332
01:12:19,207 --> 01:12:21,651
You sit around here,
and you spin your little webs,

1333
01:12:21,751 --> 01:12:24,195
and you think the whole world
revolves around you and your money.

1334
01:12:24,295 --> 01:12:25,864
Well, it doesn't, Mr. Potter.

1335
01:12:25,964 --> 01:12:29,117
In the whole vast configuration of things,

1336
01:12:29,217 --> 01:12:31,995
I'd say you were nothing
but a scurvy little spider.

1337
01:12:32,095 --> 01:12:33,087
You...

1338
01:12:34,548 --> 01:12:36,674
And that goes for you, too!

1339
01:12:40,762 --> 01:12:42,847
And it goes for you, too!

1340
01:12:49,813 --> 01:12:52,857
You wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town,

1341
01:12:53,317 --> 01:12:55,902
buying your wife a lot of fine clothes,

1342
01:12:56,153 --> 01:12:59,647
going to New York on a business trip
a couple of times a year,

1343
01:12:59,747 --> 01:13:01,991
maybe Europe once in a while.

1344
01:13:02,951 --> 01:13:05,069
I know what I'm gonna do tomorrow

1345
01:13:05,169 --> 01:13:08,364
and the next day and next year
and the year after that.

1346
01:13:08,464 --> 01:13:11,576
I'm shaking the dust
of this crummy little town off my feet,

1347
01:13:11,676 --> 01:13:13,494
and I'm gonna see the world.

1348
01:13:13,594 --> 01:13:16,331
And then I'm gonna build things.
I'm gonna build air fields.

1349
01:13:16,431 --> 01:13:19,000
I'm gonna build skyscrapers
100 stories high.

1350
01:13:19,100 --> 01:13:21,510
I'm gonna build a bridge a mile long.

1351
01:13:22,763 --> 01:13:25,932
What is it you want, Mary?
What, you want the moon?

1352
01:13:26,516 --> 01:13:28,927
If you do, just say the word,
I'll throw a lasso around it

1353
01:13:29,027 --> 01:13:30,770
and pull her down for you.

1354
01:13:30,979 --> 01:13:33,473
Buffalo gal
Won't you come out tonight?

1355
