Harry,

1434
01:18:00,086 --> 01:18:03,198
you should see what they're cooking up
in the town for you.

1435
01:18:03,298 --> 01:18:04,365
Oh, they are?

1436
01:18:04,465 --> 01:18:06,326
The Navy's gonna fly Mother home
this afternoon.

1437
01:18:06,426 --> 01:18:07,543
In a plane?

1438
01:18:07,920 --> 01:18:10,038
What? Uncle Billy?

1439
01:18:10,138 --> 01:18:12,498
- Has Uncle Billy come in yet?
- He stopped at the bank first.

1440
01:18:12,598 --> 01:18:16,044
He's not here right now, Harry.
But look, now, tell me about it.

1441
01:18:16,144 --> 01:18:17,170
- George. George, George.
- What?

1442
01:18:17,270 --> 01:18:18,379
- That man is here again.
- What man?

1443
01:18:18,479 --> 01:18:20,056
Bank examiner.

1444
01:18:21,141 --> 01:18:23,259
Harry, talk to Eustace for a minute,
will you?

1445
01:18:23,359 --> 01:18:24,552
I'll be right back.

1446
01:18:24,652 --> 01:18:26,095
- Well...
- Harry.

1447
01:18:26,195 --> 01:18:28,681
- Good morning, sir.
- Carter, bank examiner.

1448
01:18:28,781 --> 01:18:30,892
- Mr. Carter, Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1449
01:18:30,992 --> 01:18:32,727
We're all excited around here.

1450
01:18:32,827 --> 01:18:34,896
My brother just got
the Congressional Medal of Honor.

1451
01:18:34,996 --> 01:18:37,732
- The President just decorated him.
- Well, I guess they do those things.

1452
01:18:37,832 --> 01:18:40,660
- Well, I trust you had a good year.
- Good year?

1453
01:18:40,869 --> 01:18:43,996
Well, between you and me,
Mr. Carter, we're broke.

1454
01:18:44,206 --> 01:18:45,873
Yeah, very funny.

1455
01:18:48,043 --> 01:18:50,828
Well, now,
come right in here, Mr. Carter.

1456
01:18:50,928 --> 01:18:53,164
Although I shouldn't wonder
when you okay reverse charges

1457
01:18:53,264 --> 01:18:54,999
on personal long-distance calls.

1458
01:18:55,099 --> 01:18:56,668
- George, shall we hang up?
- No, no.

1459
01:18:56,768 --> 01:18:58,419
He wants to talk to Uncle Billy.
You just hold on, there.

1460
01:18:58,519 --> 01:19:01,256
Now, if you'll cooperate,
I'd like to finish with you by tonight.

1461
01:19:01,356 --> 01:19:04,217
I want to spend Christmas
in Elmira with my family.

1462
01:19:04,317 --> 01:19:05,551
I don't blame you at all, Mr. Carter.

1463
01:19:05,651 --> 01:19:06,936
Just step right in here. We'll fix you up.

1464
01:19:07,980 --> 01:19:11,023
December 24.

1465
01:19:16,613 --> 01:19:19,198
$8,000.

1466
01:19:20,325 --> 01:19:22,902
- Merry Christmas, Mr. Potter.
- Merry Christmas.

1467
01:19:23,002 --> 01:19:26,406
Well, good morning, Mr. Potter.
What's the news?

1468
01:19:26,506 --> 01:19:30,243
Well, well, well, "Harry Bailey
wins Congressional Medal."

1469
01:19:30,343 --> 01:19:32,412
That couldn't be one of the Bailey boys.

1470
01:19:32,512 --> 01:19:36,082
You just can't keep those Baileys down,
now can you, Mr. Potter?

1471
01:19:36,182 --> 01:19:38,584
How does slacker George
feel about that?

1472
01:19:38,684 --> 01:19:39,918
Very jealous. Very jealous.

1473
01:19:40,018 --> 01:19:42,212
He only lost three buttons off his vest.

1474
01:19:42,312 --> 01:19:44,339
Of course,
slacker George would've gotten

1475
01:19:44,439 --> 01:19:46,300
two of these medals if he had gone.

1476
01:19:46,400 --> 01:19:47,934
- Bad ear.
- Yes.

1477
01:19:48,102 --> 01:19:51,555
After all, Potter, some people
like George had to stay at home.

1478
01:19:51,655 --> 01:19:55,692
Not every heel was
in Germany and Japan.

1479
01:20:02,992 --> 01:20:06,703
- Good morning, Mr. Bailey.
- Good morning, Horace.

1480
01:20:07,747 --> 01:20:10,490
- I guess you forgot something.
- Huh?

1481
01:20:10,590 --> 01:20:12,409
- You forgot something.
- What?

1482
01:20:12,509 --> 01:20:13,994
Well, aren't you going
to make a deposit?

1483
01:20:14,094 --> 01:20:15,078
Oh, sure, sure I am.

1484
01:20:15,178 --> 01:20:18,590
Well, then, it's usually customary
to bring the money with you.

1485
01:20:19,133 --> 01:20:23,345
Oh, shucks, I knew I had.

1486
01:20:25,181 --> 01:20:27,257
How about that finger there?

1487
01:20:27,357 --> 01:20:28,433
Well, I...

1488
01:20:29,310 --> 01:20:30,518
Bailey.

1489
01:20:37,026 --> 01:20:39,444
Take me back there. Hurry up.

1490
01:20:41,530 --> 01:20:43,782
Come on, look sharp.

1491
01:21:01,467 --> 01:21:02,967
Take me back.

1492
01:21:12,812 --> 01:21:16,139
Just make yourself at home, Mr. Carter.
I got those books for you here.

1493
01:21:16,239 --> 01:21:17,641
Oh, hello, Vi.

1494
01:21:17,741 --> 01:21:19,309
George, can I see you for a second?

1495
01:21:19,409 --> 01:21:22,278
Why, of course you can.
Go on in the office there.

1496
01:21:22,446 --> 01:21:25,281
Uncle Billy, talk to Harry.
He's on the telephone.

1497
01:21:26,075 --> 01:21:28,860
Hurry up, Uncle Billy, hurry.
Long distance, Washington.

1498
01:21:28,960 --> 01:21:30,070
Hey, here's Harry on the phone.

1499
01:21:30,170 --> 01:21:31,905
You know, your nephew,
remember? Harry.

1500
01:21:32,005 --> 01:21:33,248
- Here he is.
- Hurry up.

1501
01:21:33,749 --> 01:21:37,502
Hello? Hello.
Yes, Harry, yes, everything's fine.

1502
01:21:38,003 --> 01:21:40,204
I ought to have my head examined.

1503
01:21:40,304 --> 01:21:43,173
$8,000. It's got to be somewhere.

1504
01:21:49,347 --> 01:21:50,597
Here you are.

1505
01:21:51,182 --> 01:21:52,266
Character?

1506
01:21:52,892 --> 01:21:54,176
If I had any character, I'd...

1507
01:21:54,276 --> 01:21:57,680
It takes a lot of character to leave
your hometown and start all over again.

1508
01:21:57,780 --> 01:21:59,265
No, George, don't.

1509
01:21:59,365 --> 01:22:01,350
Here now, you're broke, aren't you?

1510
01:22:01,450 --> 01:22:03,060
- I know, but...
- What do you want to do,

1511
01:22:03,160 --> 01:22:04,945
hock your furs and that hat?

1512
01:22:06,322 --> 01:22:07,773
You want to walk to New York?

1513
01:22:07,873 --> 01:22:09,650
You know, they charge
for meals and rent up there,

1514
01:22:09,750 --> 01:22:11,152
just the same as they do
in Bedford Falls.

1515
01:22:11,252 --> 01:22:13,036
- Yeah, sure.
- No, that's a loan, now.

1516
01:22:13,329 --> 01:22:15,622
That's my business, Building and Loan.

1517
01:22:15,790 --> 01:22:18,826
Besides, you'll get a job.
Good luck to you.

1518
01:22:18,926 --> 01:22:21,086
I'm glad I know you, George Bailey.

1519
01:22:26,301 --> 01:22:29,044
- Say hello to New York for me.
- Yeah, yeah, sure, I will.

1520
01:22:29,144 --> 01:22:31,054
Now, let's hear from you
once in a while.

1521
01:22:35,018 --> 01:22:38,312
- Merry Christmas, Vi.
- Merry Christmas, George.

1522
01:22:39,230 --> 01:22:41,682
- Mr. Bailey.
- Oh, Mr. Carter, I'm sorry.

1523
01:22:41,782 --> 01:22:43,267
I'll be right with you.
Uncle Billy in there?

1524
01:22:43,367 --> 01:22:44,852
Yeah, he's in his office.

1525
01:22:44,952 --> 01:22:47,154
What's going on?

1526
01:22:47,363 --> 01:22:49,364
The bank examiner's here.

1527
01:22:50,158 --> 01:22:53,076
- He's here?
- Yeah. He wants the accounts payable...

1528
01:22:53,203 --> 01:22:54,778
What's the matter with you?

1529
01:22:54,878 --> 01:22:56,288
Come here.

1530
01:23:16,559 --> 01:23:17,530
Eustace.

1531
01:23:17,630 --> 01:23:19,353
- Yeah?
- Come here a minute.

1532
01:23:21,105 --> 01:23:23,349
Did you see Uncle Billy
with any cash last night?

1533
01:23:23,449 --> 01:23:25,943
He had it on his desk counting it
before he closed up.

1534
01:23:27,111 --> 01:23:28,687
Now, look, did you buy anything?

1535
01:23:28,787 --> 01:23:31,065
- Nothing. Not even a stick of gum.
- All right, all right.

1536
01:23:31,165 --> 01:23:33,776
Now, we'll go over every step you took
since you left the house.

1537
01:23:33,876 --> 01:23:34,868
- Right. This way.
- Come on.

1538
01:23:44,795 --> 01:23:46,788
And did you put the envelope
in your pocket?

1539
01:23:46,888 --> 01:23:49,999
Yeah, maybe, maybe.

1540
01:23:50,099 --> 01:23:52,877
Maybe! I don't want any maybe.
We've got to find that money!

1541
01:23:52,977 --> 01:23:54,504
- I'm no good to you, George.
- Uncle Billy, look,

1542
01:23:54,604 --> 01:23:57,173
do you realize what's going
to happen if we don't find it?

1543
01:23:57,273 --> 01:23:58,299
Listen to me.

1544
01:23:58,399 --> 01:24:00,176
Do you have any secret hiding place
here in the house?

1545
01:24:00,276 --> 01:24:02,303
Someplace you would have...
Someplace you hide the money?

1546
01:24:02,403 --> 01:24:04,013
I've gone over the whole house,

1547
01:24:04,113 --> 01:24:08,017
even in rooms that have been locked
since I lost Laura.

1548
01:24:08,117 --> 01:24:11,229
Listen to me, listen to me! Think, think!

1549
01:24:11,329 --> 01:24:15,400
I can't think anymore, George.
I can't think anymore. It hurts.

1550
01:24:15,500 --> 01:24:18,403
Where's that money,
you silly, stupid old fool?

1551
01:24:18,503 --> 01:24:21,239
Where's that money?
Do you realize what this means?

1552
01:24:21,339 --> 01:24:24,333
It means bankruptcy and scandal
and prison!

1553
01:24:25,460 --> 01:24:26,744
That's what it means.

1554
01:24:26,844 --> 01:24:30,089
One of us is going to jail.
Well, it's not going to be me.

1555
01:24:52,863 --> 01:24:53,938
Hello, darling.

1556
01:24:54,038 --> 01:24:55,815
- Hello, Daddy.
- Hello, Daddy.

1557
01:24:55,915 --> 01:24:57,775
How do you like it?

1558
01:24:57,875 --> 01:24:59,535
- Bless you!
- Bless you!

1559
01:25:01,288 --> 01:25:02,447
Did you bring the wreath?

1560
01:25:02,547 --> 01:25:04,365
Yes, Daddy, did you bring
the Christmas wreath?

1561
01:25:04,465 --> 01:25:05,450
What wreath?

1562
01:25:05,550 --> 01:25:07,994
The Merry Christmas wreath
for the window.

1563
01:25:08,094 --> 01:25:09,412
No. I left it at the office.

1564
01:25:09,512 --> 01:25:11,456
- Is it snowing?
- Yeah, it just started.

1565
01:25:11,556 --> 01:25:14,634
- Where's your coat and hat?
- Left them at the office.

1566
01:25:14,801 --> 01:25:15,877
What's the matter?

1567
01:25:15,977 --> 01:25:18,554
Nothing's the matter.
Everything's all right.

1568
01:25:26,229 --> 01:25:29,515
Come on, Pete, you're a big boy.
You can help me get this star up.

1569
01:25:29,615 --> 01:25:32,610
Way up at the top. There. That's it.

1570
01:25:33,236 --> 01:25:37,031
All right, fill in that little bare spot
right there. Right there.

1571
01:25:39,242 --> 01:25:42,736
Isn't it wonderful about Harry?
We're famous, George.

1572
01:25:42,836 --> 01:25:46,581
Bet I had 50 calls today
about the parade, the banquet.

1573
01:25:46,749 --> 01:25:48,833
Your mother's so excited. She...

1574
01:26:09,438 --> 01:26:11,932
Must she keep playing that?

1575
01:26:12,032 --> 01:26:14,851
I have to practice it
for the party tonight, Daddy.

1576
01:26:14,951 --> 01:26:18,021
Mama said we could stay up
till midnight and sing Christmas carols.

1577
01:26:18,121 --> 01:26:19,614
Can you sing, Daddy?

1578
01:26:19,990 --> 01:26:21,566
Better hurry and shave.

1579
01:26:21,666 --> 01:26:24,611
- The families will be here soon.
- Families.

1580
01:26:24,711 --> 01:26:27,163
I don't want the families over here.

1581
01:26:28,958 --> 01:26:31,993
Come on out in the kitchen with me
while I finish dinner.

1582
01:26:32,093 --> 01:26:35,171
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1583
01:26:35,297 --> 01:26:37,416
- Have a hectic day?
- Oh, yeah.

1584
01:26:37,516 --> 01:26:40,427
Another big red-letter day
for the Baileys.

1585
01:26:40,886 --> 01:26:43,714
Daddy, the Browns next door
have a new car. You should see it.

1586
01:26:43,814 --> 01:26:46,049
Well, what's the matter with our car?
Isn't it good enough for you?

1587
01:26:46,149 --> 01:26:47,225
Yes, Daddy.

1588
01:26:47,476 --> 01:26:49,886
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1589
01:26:49,986 --> 01:26:52,230
- Excuse you for what?
- I burped.

1590
01:26:53,315 --> 01:26:54,725
All right, darling, you're excused.

1591
01:26:54,825 --> 01:26:57,569
Now, go on upstairs
and see if little Zuzu wants anything.

1592
01:26:58,112 --> 01:27:02,399
- Zuzu? What's the matter with Zuzu?
- Oh, she's just got a cold. She's in bed.

1593
01:27:02,499 --> 01:27:03,942
Caught it coming home from school.

1594
01:27:04,042 --> 01:27:06,570
They gave her a flower for a prize,
and she didn't want to crush it,

1595
01:27:06,670 --> 01:27:07,904
so she didn't button up her coat.

1596
01:27:08,004 --> 01:27:10,157
- What is it, a sore throat or what?
- It's just a cold.

1597
01:27:10,257 --> 01:27:11,533
- The doctor says it's nothing serious.
- The doctor?

1598
01:27:11,633 --> 01:27:13,368
- Was the doctor here?
- Yes, I called him right away.

1599
01:27:13,468 --> 01:27:14,703
He says it's nothing to worry about.

1600
01:27:14,803 --> 01:27:16,079
Is she running a temperature?
What is it?

1601
01:27:16,179 --> 01:27:18,248
Just a teensy one, 99.6.
She'll be all right.

1602
01:27:18,348 --> 01:27:19,791
Of course, it's this old house.

1603
01:27:19,891 --> 01:27:22,085
I don't know why
we don't all have pneumonia.

1604
01:27:22,185 --> 01:27:26,514
Drafty old barn.
Might as well be living in a refrigerator.

1605
01:27:26,724 --> 01:27:28,467
Why did we have
to live here in the first place

1606
01:27:28,567 --> 01:27:31,686
and stay around this measly,
crummy old town?

1607
01:27:32,480 --> 01:27:35,056
- George, what's wrong?
- Wrong! Everything's wrong.

1608
01:27:35,156 --> 01:27:38,435
You call this a happy family?
Why do we have to have all these kids?

1609
01:27:38,535 --> 01:27:42,188
- Dad, how do you spell "frankincense"?
- I don't know. Ask your mother.

1610
01:27:42,288 --> 01:27:44,023
- Where're you going?
- I'm going up to see Zuzu.

1611
01:27:44,123 --> 01:27:46,533
He told me to write a play for tomorrow.

1612
01:27:57,378 --> 01:28:01,131
F-r-a-n-k-i-n...

1613
01:28:01,341 --> 01:28:02,716
Hi, Daddy!

1614
01:28:03,843 --> 01:28:07,054
- Well, what happened to you?
- I won a flower.

1615
01:28:07,347 --> 01:28:09,173
Wait now.
Where do you think you're going?

1616
01:28:09,273 --> 01:28:10,925
I want to give my flower a drink.

1617
01:28:11,025 --> 01:28:13,219
All right, all right.
Now, give Daddy the flower.

1618
01:28:13,319 --> 01:28:14,637
I'll give it a drink.

1619
01:28:14,737 --> 01:28:16,063
Now, here.

1620
01:28:17,565 --> 01:28:19,642
Look, Daddy!

1621
01:28:19,742 --> 01:28:21,143
Paste it!

1622
01:28:21,243 --> 01:28:23,779
Yeah, all right, all right. Give it here.

1623
01:28:26,241 --> 01:28:28,784
Now, we'll paste this together here.

1624
01:28:31,996 --> 01:28:35,157
There. There it is. Good as new.

1625
01:28:35,257 --> 01:28:37,326
Now, give the flower a drink.

1626
01:28:37,426 --> 01:28:38,869
Now, will you do something for me?

1627
01:28:38,969 --> 01:28:41,713
- What?
- Will you try to get some sleep?

1628
01:28:41,923 --> 01:28:44,834
I'm not sleepy.
I want to look at my flower.

1629
01:28:44,934 --> 01:28:49,346
I know, I know, but you just go to sleep
and then you can dream about it,

1630
01:28:49,639 --> 01:28:51,799
and it'll be a whole garden.

1631
01:28:51,899 --> 01:28:53,141
It will?

1632
01:29:01,568 --> 01:29:03,352
- Telephone!
- Telephone!

1633
01:29:03,452 --> 01:29:04,862
I'll get it.

1634
01:29:06,781 --> 01:29:07,948
Hello?

1635
01:29:08,867 --> 01:29:10,909
Yes, this is Mrs. Bailey.

1636
01:29:11,286 --> 01:29:14,154
Oh, thank you, Mrs. Welch.
I'm sure she'll be all right.

1637
01:29:14,254 --> 01:29:15,865
The doctor said
that she ought to be out of bed

1638
01:29:15,965 --> 01:29:17,157
in time to have her Christmas dinner.

1639
01:29:17,257 --> 01:29:18,784
- Is that Zuzu's teacher?
- Yes.

1640
01:29:18,884 --> 01:29:20,202
Let me speak to her.

1641
01:29:20,302 --> 01:29:22,754
Hello. Hello, Mrs. Welch?

1642
01:29:23,047 --> 01:29:25,583
This is George Bailey. I'm Zuzu's father.

1643
01:29:25,683 --> 01:29:27,376
Say, what kind of a teacher
are you, anyway?

1644
01:29:27,476 --> 01:29:29,753
What do you mean
sending her home like that, half naked?

1645
01:29:29,853 --> 01:29:32,381
Do you realize she'll probably end up
with pneumonia on account of you?

1646
01:29:32,481 --> 01:29:34,425
- George!
- Is this the sort of thing we pay taxes for

1647
01:29:34,525 --> 01:29:36,635
to have teachers like you?

1648
01:29:36,735 --> 01:29:39,972
Stupid, silly, careless people who send
our kids home without any clothes on?

1649
01:29:40,072 --> 01:29:41,890
You know, maybe my kids
aren't the best-dressed kids.

1650
01:29:41,990 --> 01:29:43,725
And maybe they don't have
any decent clothes...

1651
01:29:43,825 --> 01:29:45,610
That stupid...

1652
01:29:46,320 --> 01:29:49,230
Hello, Mrs. Welch. I want to apologize...

1653
01:29:49,330 --> 01:29:51,449
Hello? Hello.

1654
01:29:53,201 --> 01:29:55,612
- She's hung up!
- I'll hang her up!

1655
01:29:55,712 --> 01:29:58,907
- Hey, you! I'll knock your block off!
- What is that?

1656
01:29:59,007 --> 01:30:00,783
Hello! Who's this?

1657
01:30:00,883 --> 01:30:02,418
Oh, Mr. Welch?

1658
01:30:02,794 --> 01:30:04,245
Okay, that's fine, Mr. Welch.

1659
01:30:04,345 --> 01:30:06,414
Give me a chance to tell you
what I really think of your wife.

1660
01:30:06,514 --> 01:30:07,540
George, stop it.

1661
01:30:07,640 --> 01:30:09,334
Will you get out and let me handle this?

1662
01:30:09,434 --> 01:30:11,969
Hello? Hello? What?

1663
01:30:13,680 --> 01:30:15,256
Oh, you will, huh?

1664
01:30:15,356 --> 01:30:18,259
Okay, Mr. Welch. Any time
you think you're man enough, you...

1665
01:30:18,359 --> 01:30:19,852
Hello! Any...

1666
01:30:24,024 --> 01:30:24,995
Dad, how do you spell "hallelujah"?

1667
01:30:25,095 --> 01:30:27,101
How should I know?
What do you think I am, a dictionary?

1668
01:30:27,201 --> 01:30:28,436
Tommy, stop that! Stop it!

1669
01:30:28,536 --> 01:30:30,396
Janie, haven't you learned
that silly tune yet?

1670
01:30:30,496 --> 01:30:34,200
You play it over and over again.
Now stop it! Stop it!

1671
01:31:01,311 --> 01:31:02,937
I'm sorry, Mary.

1672
01:31:06,233 --> 01:31:08,109
Janie, I'm sorry.

1673
01:31:08,777 --> 01:31:12,947
I didn't mean that. I...
You go on and practice.

1674
01:31:18,495 --> 01:31:20,871
Pete, I owe you an apology, too.

1675
01:31:22,124 --> 01:31:23,499
I'm sorry.

1676
01:31:24,918 --> 01:31:27,753
- What do you want to know?
- Nothing, Daddy.

1677
01:31:34,720 --> 01:31:36,504
What's the matter with everybody?

1678
01:31:36,604 --> 01:31:39,132
Janie, go on. I told you to practice.
Now, go on, play!

1679
01:31:39,232 --> 01:31:40,558
Oh, Daddy!

1680
01:31:45,938 --> 01:31:49,399
George, why must you
torture the children? Why don't you...

1681
01:31:50,151 --> 01:31:51,401
Mary...

1682
01:32:05,458 --> 01:32:07,367
Bedford 247, please.

1683
01:32:07,467 --> 01:32:09,494
- Is Daddy in trouble?
- Yes, Pete.

1684
01:32:09,594 --> 01:32:12,664
- Shall I pray for him?
- Yes, Janie, pray very hard.

1685
01:32:12,764 --> 01:32:14,799
- Me, too?
- You, too, Tommy.

1686
01:32:15,801 --> 01:32:17,761
Hello? Uncle Billy?

1687
01:32:19,055 --> 01:32:20,096
I'm in trouble, Mr. Potter.

1688
01:32:20,639 --> 01:32:22,057
I need help.

1689
01:32:23,142 --> 01:32:26,011
Through some sort of an accident,
my company's short in their accounts.

1690
01:32:26,111 --> 01:32:27,888
The bank examiner got there today.

1691
01:32:27,988 --> 01:32:30,223
I've got to raise $8,000 immediately.

1692
01:32:30,323 --> 01:32:32,768
Oh, that's what the reporters wanted
to talk to you about?

1693
01:32:32,868 --> 01:32:34,186
- The reporters?
- Yes.

1694
01:32:34,286 --> 01:32:37,655
They called me up
from your Building and Loan.

1695
01:32:37,948 --> 01:32:41,318
Oh, there's a man over there
from the D.A.'s office, too.

1696
01:32:41,418 --> 01:32:42,611
He's looking for you.

1697
01:32:42,711 --> 01:32:46,323
Please help me, Mr. Potter.
Help me, won't you, please?

1698
01:32:46,423 --> 01:32:48,241
Can't you see what it means
to my family?

1699
01:32:48,341 --> 01:32:51,161
I'll pay any sort of a bonus on the loan,
any interest,

1700
01:32:51,261 --> 01:32:52,829
if you still want the Building and Loan...

1701
01:32:52,929 --> 01:32:56,416
George, could it possibly be there's
a slight discrepancy in the books?

1702
01:32:56,516 --> 01:32:58,043
No, sir.
There's nothing wrong with the books.

1703
01:32:58,143 --> 01:33:01,129
I've just misplaced $8,000.
I can't find it anywhere.

1704
01:33:01,229 --> 01:33:05,183
- You misplaced $8,000?
- Yes, sir.

1705
01:33:08,354 --> 01:33:11,890
- Have you notified the police?
- No, sir. I didn't want the publicity.

1706
01:33:11,990 --> 01:33:16,061
- Harry's homecoming tomorrow...
- They're going to believe that one.

1707
01:33:16,161 --> 01:33:18,438
What've you been doing, George?

1708
01:33:18,538 --> 01:33:20,232
Playing the market
with the company's money?

1709
01:33:20,332 --> 01:33:21,441
No, sir. No, sir, I haven't.

1710
01:33:21,541 --> 01:33:23,527
Is it a woman, then?

1711
01:33:23,627 --> 01:33:27,197
You know, it's all over town that
you've been giving money to Violet Bick.

1712
01:33:27,297 --> 01:33:28,323
What?

1713
01:33:28,423 --> 01:33:31,118
Not that it makes any difference to me,
but why did you come to me?

1714
01:33:31,218 --> 01:33:33,954
Why don't you go to Sam Wainwright
and ask him for the money?

1715
01:33:34,054 --> 01:33:35,622
I can't get a hold of him. He's in Europe.

1716
01:33:35,722 --> 01:33:37,124
Well, what about all your other friends?

1717
01:33:37,224 --> 01:33:39,543
They don't have that kind of money,
Mr. Potter. You know that.

1718
01:33:39,643 --> 01:33:41,552
You're the only one in town
that can help me.

1719
01:33:42,762 --> 01:33:46,056
I've suddenly become quite important.

1720
01:33:46,891 --> 01:33:49,552
What kind of security
would I have, George?

1721
01:33:49,652 --> 01:33:52,972
- Have you got any stocks?
- No, sir.

1722
01:33:53,072 --> 01:33:55,899
Bonds? Real estate?
Collateral of any kind?

1723
01:33:56,401 --> 01:34:00,604
I have some life insurance,
a $15,000 policy.

1724
01:34:00,704 --> 01:34:04,408
- Yes. How much is your equity in it?
- Five hundred dollars.

1725
01:34:04,576 --> 01:34:06,410
Five hundred dollars?

1726
01:34:06,828 --> 01:34:09,454
And you ask me to lend you $8,000?

1727
01:34:11,040 --> 01:34:14,126
Look at you. You used to be so cocky.

1728
01:34:14,460 --> 01:34:17,546
You were going to go out
and conquer the world.

1729
01:34:18,089 --> 01:34:22,885
You once called me a warped,
frustrated old man.

1730
01:34:23,595 --> 01:34:26,930
What are you but a warped,
frustrated young man?

1731
01:34:27,515 --> 01:34:29,091
A miserable little clerk,

1732
01:34:29,191 --> 01:34:30,843
crawling in here
on your hands and knees

1733
01:34:30,943 --> 01:34:32,811
and begging for help.

1734
01:34:33,021 --> 01:34:34,930
No securities, no stocks, no bonds.

1735
01:34:35,030 --> 01:34:38,684
Nothing but a miserable
little $500 equity

1736
01:34:38,784 --> 01:34:40,944
in a life insurance policy.

1737
01:34:41,779 --> 01:34:44,198
You're worth more dead than alive.

1738
01:34:44,657 --> 01:34:47,651
Why don't you go to the riffraff
you love so much

1739
01:34:47,751 --> 01:34:50,287
and ask them to let you have $8,000?

1740
01:34:50,705 --> 01:34:51,906
You know why?

1741
01:34:52,006 --> 01:34:54,700
Because they'd run you
out of town on a rail.

1742
01:34:54,800 --> 01:34:57,995
But I tell you
what I'm going to do for you, George.

1743
01:34:58,095 --> 01:35:01,248
Since the state examiner is still here,

1744
01:35:01,348 --> 01:35:03,876
as a stockholder
of the Building and Loan,

1745
01:35:03,976 --> 01:35:06,929
I'm going to swear out
a warrant for your arrest.

1746
01:35:07,305 --> 01:35:11,350
Misappropriation of funds,
manipulation, malfeasance.

1747
01:35:12,977 --> 01:35:15,346
All right, George, go ahead.

1748
01:35:15,446 --> 01:35:18,315
You can't hide in a little town like this.

1749
01:35:18,566 --> 01:35:20,776
Yeah, Bill? This is Potter.

1750
01:35:34,540 --> 01:35:37,834
Merry Christmas! Glad you come!

1751
01:35:38,378 --> 01:35:40,037
How about some of that good spaghetti?

1752
01:35:40,137 --> 01:35:41,837
We got everything.

1753
01:35:52,933 --> 01:35:54,183
Oh, God.

1754
01:35:57,521 --> 01:35:58,771
Oh, God.

1755
01:36:03,819 --> 01:36:05,695
Dear Father in Heaven,

1756
01:36:08,865 --> 01:36:10,825
I'm not a praying man,

1757
01:36:11,994 --> 01:36:14,912
but if you're up there
and you can hear me,

1758
01:36:16,540 --> 01:36:18,165
show me the way.

1759
01:36:18,625 --> 01:36:20,960
I'm at the end of my rope. I...

1760
01:36:22,879 --> 01:36:24,839
Show me the way, O God.

1761
01:36:29,720 --> 01:36:33,389
Are you all right, George?
Want somebody to take you home?

1762
01:36:36,059 --> 01:36:38,428
Why you drink so much, my friend?

1763
01:36:38,528 --> 01:36:41,897
Please go home, Mr. Bailey.
This is Christmas Eve.

1764
01:36:42,399 --> 01:36:44,900
Bailey? Which Bailey?

1765
01:36:45,527 --> 01:36:47,570
This is Mr. George Bailey.

1766
01:36:51,783 --> 01:36:54,652
The next time you talk to my wife
like that, you'll get worse!

1767
01:36:54,752 --> 01:36:56,070
She cried for an hour!

1768
01:36:56,170 --> 01:36:59,324
It isn't enough she slaves teaching
your stupid kids how to read and write,

1769
01:36:59,424 --> 01:37:01,951
- and you have to bawl her out.
- You get out of here, Mr. Welch!

1770
01:37:02,051 --> 01:37:03,494
Now, wait, I want to pay for my drink.

1771
01:37:03,594 --> 01:37:05,246
Never mind the money!
You get out of here quick!

1772
01:37:05,346 --> 01:37:08,299
- All right!
- You hit my best friend! Get out!

1773
01:37:13,638 --> 01:37:16,265
- You all right, George?
- Who was that?

1774
01:37:16,683 --> 01:37:19,761
He gone. No worry. He name is Welch.

1775
01:37:19,861 --> 01:37:22,638
- He no come into my place no more.
- Oh, Welch.

1776
01:37:22,738 --> 01:37:24,640
That's what I get for praying.

1777
01:37:24,740 --> 01:37:26,768
The last time he come in here.
You hear that, Nick?

1778
01:37:26,868 --> 01:37:27,977
Yes, you bet.

1779
01:37:28,077 --> 01:37:31,481
Where's my insurance policy?
Oh, here it is.

1780
01:37:31,581 --> 01:37:33,274
Oh, no, please,
don't go this way, Mr. Bailey.

1781
01:37:33,374 --> 01:37:35,026
- I'm all right.
- No, no, you no feel so good.

1782
01:37:35,126 --> 01:37:36,486
- Sit down and rest.
- I'm all right.

1783
01:37:36,586 --> 01:37:38,662
Please no go away, please!

1784
01:37:57,139 --> 01:37:59,474
What do you think you're doing?

1785
01:38:01,560 --> 01:38:05,438
Now look what you did.
My great-grandfather planted this tree!

1786
01:38:06,315 --> 01:38:08,316
Hey, you! Hey, you!

1787
01:38:09,068 --> 01:38:12,821
Come back here, you drunken fool!
Get this car out of here!

1788
01:38:20,746 --> 01:38:24,332
Hey, what's the matter with you?
Look where you're going.

1789
01:39:11,172 --> 01:39:12,297
Help!

1790
01:39:13,883 --> 01:39:16,551
Help! Help!

1791
01:39:20,055 --> 01:39:21,890
Help! Help!

1792
01:39:24,518 --> 01:39:26,144
Help!

1793
01:39:29,064 --> 01:39:32,984
Help! Help! Help! Help!

1794
01:39:39,158 --> 01:39:41,451
Help! Help!

1795
01:39:58,384 --> 01:40:00,669
I didn't have time
to get some stylish underwear.

1796
01:40:00,769 --> 01:40:03,555
Wife gave me this
on my last birthday.

1797
01:40:04,224 --> 01:40:05,974
I passed away in it.

1798
01:40:09,562 --> 01:40:12,439
Oh, Tom Sawyer's drying out, too.

1799
01:40:15,610 --> 01:40:19,071
You should read the new book
Mark Twain's writing now.

1800
01:40:19,739 --> 01:40:21,607
How did you happen to fall in?

1801
01:40:21,707 --> 01:40:24,868
I didn't fall in.
I jumped in to save George.

1802
01:40:25,161 --> 01:40:28,080
You what? To save me?

1803
01:40:28,289 --> 01:40:31,367
Well, I did, didn't I?
You didn't go through with it, did you?

1804
01:40:31,467 --> 01:40:33,577
- Go through with what?
- Suicide.

1805
01:40:33,677 --> 01:40:36,747
It's against the law
to commit suicide around here.

1806
01:40:36,847 --> 01:40:39,667
Yeah, it's against the law
where I come from, too.

1807
01:40:39,767 --> 01:40:42,135
- Where do you come from?
- Heaven.

1808
01:40:47,267 --> 01:40:50,261
I had to act quickly.
That's why I jumped in.

1809
01:40:50,361 --> 01:40:52,763
I knew if I were drowning,
you'd try to save me.

1810
01:40:52,863 --> 01:40:55,816
You see, you did,
and that's how I saved you.

1811
01:40:56,526 --> 01:40:57,943
Very funny.

1812
01:40:58,152 --> 01:41:00,229
Your lip's bleeding, George.

1813
01:41:00,329 --> 01:41:04,400
Yeah, I got a bust in the jaw
in answer to a prayer a little bit ago.

1814
01:41:04,500 --> 01:41:08,320
Oh, no, no, no, George,
I'm the answer to your prayer.

1815
01:41:08,420 --> 01:41:10,747
That's why I was sent down here.

1816
01:41:11,332 --> 01:41:14,493
- How'd you know my name?
- Oh, I know all about you.

1817
01:41:14,593 --> 01:41:16,412
I've watched you grow up
from a little boy.

1818
01:41:16,512 --> 01:41:17,913
What are you,
a mind reader or something?

1819
01:41:18,013 --> 01:41:19,123
No.

1820
01:41:19,223 --> 01:41:23,176
- Well, who are you then?
- Clarence Oddbody, AS2.

1821
01:41:23,845 --> 01:41:25,178
Oddbody?

1822
01:41:26,222 --> 01:41:28,348
AS2? What's that, AS2?

1823
01:41:28,600 --> 01:41:30,350
Angel Second Class.

1824
01:41:40,737 --> 01:41:42,529
Cheerio, my good man.

1825
01:41:46,700 --> 01:41:48,117
Oh, brother.

1826
01:41:50,412 --> 01:41:51,704
Gee whiz.

1827
01:41:52,706 --> 01:41:55,541
I wonder what Martini
put in those drinks.

1828
01:41:57,586 --> 01:42:02,131
Hey, what's with you?
What did you say just a minute ago?

1829
01:42:02,424 --> 01:42:04,042
Why'd you want to save me?

1830
01:42:04,142 --> 01:42:07,720
That's what I was sent down for.
I'm your guardian angel.

1831
01:42:08,138 --> 01:42:10,256
I wouldn't be a bit surprised.

1832
01:42:10,356 --> 01:42:14,677
Ridiculous of you to think
of killing yourself for money, $8,000.

1833
01:42:14,777 --> 01:42:17,805
Yeah, now, just things like that...
How do you know that?

1834
01:42:17,905 --> 01:42:21,942
I told you. I'm your guardian angel.
I know everything about you.

1835
01:42:22,944 --> 01:42:26,064
Well, you look about
like the kind of an angel I'd get.

1836
01:42:26,164 --> 01:42:29,108
Sort of a fallen angel, aren't you?
What happened to your wings?

1837
01:42:29,208 --> 01:42:33,245
I haven't won my wings yet.
That's why I'm an Angel Second Class.

1838
01:42:37,542 --> 01:42:39,077
I don't know whether I'd like it very much

1839
01:42:39,177 --> 01:42:41,120
being seen around
with an angel without any wings.

1840
01:42:41,220 --> 01:42:44,832
Oh, I've got to earn them,
and you'll help me, won't you?

1841
01:42:44,932 --> 01:42:46,300
Sure, sure.

1842
01:42:46,802 --> 01:42:49,428
- How?
- By letting me help you.

1843
01:42:49,638 --> 01:42:52,423
Yes. Only one way you can help me.

1844
01:42:52,523 --> 01:42:54,467
You don't happen to have
8,000 bucks on you, do you?

1845
01:42:54,567 --> 01:42:57,011
Oh, no. No.
We don't use money in heaven.

1846
01:42:57,111 --> 01:42:59,647
Oh, yeah, that's right, I keep forgetting.

1847
01:43:00,357 --> 01:43:03,984
- Comes in pretty handy down here, bub.
- Oh, tut, tut, tut.

1848
01:43:05,028 --> 01:43:07,279
I found it out a little late.

1849
01:43:07,656 --> 01:43:09,691
I'm worth more dead than alive.

1850
01:43:09,791 --> 01:43:13,945
Now, look, you mustn't talk like that.
I won't get my wings with that attitude.

1851
01:43:14,045 --> 01:43:17,699
You just don't know all that you've done.
If it hadn't been for you...

1852
01:43:17,799 --> 01:43:20,493
Yeah, if it hadn't been for me,
everybody'd be a lot better off.

1853
01:43:20,593 --> 01:43:22,787
My wife and my kids and my friends.

1854
01:43:22,887 --> 01:43:26,124
I mean, look, little fellow, go off
and haunt somebody else, will you?

1855
01:43:26,224 --> 01:43:28,876
No, now, you don't understand.
I've got my job...

1856
01:43:28,976 --> 01:43:30,803
Oh, shut up, will you?

1857
01:43:34,683 --> 01:43:37,393
Oh, this isn't gonna be so easy.

1858
01:43:42,315 --> 01:43:46,818
Yeah, so you still think killing yourself
would make everyone feel happier, eh?

1859
01:43:48,612 --> 01:43:51,406
Well, I don't know. I guess you're right.

1860
01:43:52,700 --> 01:43:55,569
I suppose it would have been better
if I'd never been born at all.

1861
01:43:55,669 --> 01:43:58,989
- What'd you say?
- I said I wish I'd never been born.

1862
01:43:59,089 --> 01:44:01,708
Oh, you mustn't say things like that.

1863
01:44:02,168 --> 01:44:06,755
You... Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
That's an idea.

1864
01:44:07,715 --> 01:44:09,382
What do you think?

1865
01:44:10,009 --> 01:44:11,801
Yeah, that'll do it.

1866
01:44:12,470 --> 01:44:13,803
All right.

1867
01:44:16,515 --> 01:44:19,726
You've got your wish.
You've never been born.

1868
01:44:25,316 --> 01:44:28,359
You don't have
to make all that fuss about it!

1869
01:44:29,236 --> 01:44:30,645
What did you say?

1870
01:44:30,745 --> 01:44:34,608
You've never been born. You don't exist.
You haven't a care in the world.

1871
01:44:34,708 --> 01:44:37,944
No worries, no obligations,
no $8,000 to get,

1872
01:44:38,044 --> 01:44:39,905
no Potter looking for you
with the Sheriff.

1873
01:44:40,005 --> 01:44:43,450
- Say something else in that ear.
- Sure, you can hear out of it.

1874
01:44:43,550 --> 01:44:45,660
Well, that's the doggonedest thing.

1875
01:44:45,760 --> 01:44:48,288
I haven't heard anything out of that ear
since I was a kid.

1876
01:44:48,388 --> 01:44:50,540
Must have been that jump
in that cold water.

1877
01:44:50,640 --> 01:44:53,384
Your lip stopped bleeding, too, George.

1878
01:44:58,057 --> 01:45:01,768
What do you know about that?
What's happening?

1879
01:45:03,229 --> 01:45:05,514
It stopped snowing out here, didn't it?

1880
01:45:05,614 --> 01:45:07,398
What's happened here?

1881
01:45:08,108 --> 01:45:10,018
What I need
is a couple of good stiff drinks.

1882
01:45:10,118 --> 01:45:12,403
How about you, Angel?
You want a drink?

1883
01:45:13,906 --> 01:45:16,149
Come on,
soon as these clothes of ours are dry...

1884
01:45:16,249 --> 01:45:18,193
The clothes are dry.

1885
01:45:18,293 --> 01:45:21,446
What do you know about that?
Stove's hotter than I thought.

1886
01:45:21,546 --> 01:45:25,659
Now, come on, get your clothes on.
We'll stroll up to my car and get...

1887
01:45:25,759 --> 01:45:27,911
Oh, I'm sorry. I'll stroll. You fly.

1888
01:45:28,011 --> 01:45:29,538
I can't fly. I haven't got my wings.

1889
01:45:29,638 --> 01:45:32,340
You haven't got your wings.
Yeah, that's right.

1890
01:45:37,972 --> 01:45:39,339
What's the matter?

1891
01:45:39,439 --> 01:45:42,133
Well, this is where I left my car,
and it isn't here.

1892
01:45:42,233 --> 01:45:45,511
- You have no car.
- Well, I had a car, and it was right here.

1893
01:45:45,611 --> 01:45:47,137
I guess somebody moved it.

1894
01:45:47,237 --> 01:45:51,316
- Good evening.
- Oh, say, hey, where's my car?

1895
01:45:51,568 --> 01:45:53,686
- I beg your pardon?
- My car, my car.

1896
01:45:53,786 --> 01:45:56,021
I'm the fellow that owns the car
that ran into your tree.

1897
01:45:56,121 --> 01:45:58,148
- What tree?
- What do you mean, what tree?

1898
01:45:58,248 --> 01:46:00,317
This tree. Here, I ran into it.

1899
01:46:00,417 --> 01:46:03,620
Cut a big gash in the side of it there.

1900
01:46:07,959 --> 01:46:11,412
You must mean two other trees.
You had me worried.

1901
01:46:11,512 --> 01:46:13,706
One of the oldest trees in Pottersville.

1902
01:46:13,806 --> 01:46:14,957
Pottersville?

1903
01:46:15,057 --> 01:46:16,667
Why, you mean Bedford Falls.

1904
01:46:16,767 --> 01:46:20,304
I mean Pottersville.
Don't you think I know where I live?

1905
01:46:20,471 --> 01:46:22,548
What's the matter with you?

1906
01:46:22,648 --> 01:46:25,851
What's the matter with me?
Well, I guess I just...

1907
01:46:28,438 --> 01:46:32,733
Oh, I don't know.
Either I'm off my nut or he is or you are.

1908
01:46:33,735 --> 01:46:35,060
It isn't me.

1909
01:46:35,160 --> 01:46:37,187
Well, maybe I left the car
up at Martini's.

1910
01:46:37,287 --> 01:46:39,607
- Well, come on, Gabriel.
- Clarence.

1911
01:46:39,707 --> 01:46:41,491
Clarence. Clarence.

1912
01:46:46,956 --> 01:46:50,792
That's all right. Go on in.
Martini is a friend of mine.

1913
01:46:51,169 --> 01:46:53,837
There's a place to sit down. Sit down.

1914
01:47:00,178 --> 01:47:03,714
- Oh, hello, Nick. Hey, where's Martini?
- Want a martini?

1915
01:47:03,814 --> 01:47:05,841
No, no, Martini. Your boss.
Where is he?

1916
01:47:05,941 --> 01:47:08,344
Hey, look, I'm the boss.
You want a drink or don't you?

1917
01:47:08,444 --> 01:47:10,638
Okay, all right. Double bourbon,
will you, and quick, huh?

1918
01:47:10,738 --> 01:47:11,980
Okay.

1919
01:47:15,109 --> 01:47:18,195
- What's yours?
- I was just thinking.

1920
01:47:19,364 --> 01:47:21,774
It's been so long since I...

1921
01:47:21,874 --> 01:47:25,527
Look, mister, I'm standing here
waiting for you to make up your mind.

1922
01:47:25,627 --> 01:47:27,237
That's a good man.

1923
01:47:27,337 --> 01:47:29,498
I was just thinking

1924
01:47:30,375 --> 01:47:33,543
of a flaming rum punch.

1925
01:47:33,878 --> 01:47:36,413
No, it's not cold enough for that,
not nearly cold enough.

1926
01:47:36,513 --> 01:47:39,458
Wait a minute. Wait a minute. I got it.

1927
01:47:39,558 --> 01:47:43,128
Mulled wine, heavy on the cinnamon
and light on the cloves.

1928
01:47:43,228 --> 01:47:45,129
Off with you, me lad, and be lively!

1929
01:47:45,229 --> 01:47:48,257
Hey, look, mister,
we serve hard drinks in here

1930
01:47:48,357 --> 01:47:50,134
for men who want to get drunk fast.

1931
01:47:50,234 --> 01:47:53,763
And we don't need any characters
around to give the joint atmosphere.

1932
01:47:53,863 --> 01:47:57,475
Is that clear, or do I have
to slip you my left for a convincer?

1933
01:47:57,575 --> 01:47:58,935
What's he talking about?

1934
01:47:59,035 --> 01:48:02,897
Nick, Nick,
just give him the same as mine.

1935
01:48:02,997 --> 01:48:05,324
- He's okay.
- Okay.

1936
01:48:06,743 --> 01:48:10,321
What's the matter with him?
I never saw Nick act like that before.

1937
01:48:10,421 --> 01:48:13,541
You'll see a lot of strange things
from now on.

1938
01:48:13,792 --> 01:48:15,584
Oh, yeah.

1939
01:48:18,755 --> 01:48:22,375
Hey, little fellow,
you worry me, you know.

1940
01:48:22,475 --> 01:48:25,420
- You got someplace to sleep?
- No.

1941
01:48:25,520 --> 01:48:27,046
You don't, huh?

1942
01:48:27,146 --> 01:48:29,765
- Well, you got any money?
- No.

1943
01:48:30,726 --> 01:48:32,343
No wonder you jumped in the river.

1944
01:48:32,443 --> 01:48:36,105
I jumped in the river to save you
so I could get my wings.

1945
01:48:39,943 --> 01:48:42,061
- Somebody's just made it.
- Made what?

1946
01:48:42,161 --> 01:48:46,949
Every time you hear a bell ring, it means
that some angel's just got his wings.

1947
01:48:54,833 --> 01:48:57,577
Look, I think maybe you
better not mention

1948
01:48:57,677 --> 01:48:59,037
getting your wings around here.

1949
01:48:59,137 --> 01:49:01,547
Why? Don't they believe in angels?

1950
01:49:04,134 --> 01:49:05,960
Yeah, they believe in them.

1951
01:49:06,060 --> 01:49:09,346
Oh, why should they be surprised
when they see one?

1952
01:49:11,141 --> 01:49:14,393
Oh, he never grew up. He's...

1953
01:49:14,811 --> 01:49:18,814
- How old are you anyway, Clarence?
- Two hundred and ninety-three,

1954
01:49:21,026 --> 01:49:22,318
next May.

1955
01:49:22,903 --> 01:49:25,521
That does it. Out, you two pixies!

1956
01:49:25,621 --> 01:49:27,565
Go through the door or out the window.

1957
01:49:27,665 --> 01:49:29,734
- Look, Nick, what's wrong?
- Now, that's another thing.

1958
01:49:29,834 --> 01:49:31,778
Where do you come off
calling me Nick?

1959
01:49:31,878 --> 01:49:33,362
Well, Nick, that's your name.

1960
01:49:33,462 --> 01:49:37,575
What's that got to do with it?
I don't know you from Adam's off ox.

1961
01:49:37,675 --> 01:49:40,544
Hey. Hey, you rummy, there.
Come here, come here.

1962
01:49:44,007 --> 01:49:47,592
Didn't I tell you never to come
panhandling around here, huh?

1963
01:49:54,683 --> 01:49:56,017
Mr. Gower.

1964
01:49:57,269 --> 01:49:58,603
Mr. Gower.

1965
01:50:00,231 --> 01:50:01,981
What... What did...

1966
01:50:02,358 --> 01:50:04,776
Mr. Gower, look, this is George Bailey.

1967
01:50:06,153 --> 01:50:08,279
- Don't you know me?
- No.

1968
01:50:09,865 --> 01:50:11,066
No.

1969
01:50:11,166 --> 01:50:12,609
Throw him out. Throw him out.

1970
01:50:12,709 --> 01:50:14,702
Mr. Gower! Hey, what is...

1971
01:50:15,871 --> 01:50:18,115
Hey, Nick. Nick.
Isn't that Mr. Gower, the druggist?

1972
01:50:18,215 --> 01:50:20,450
You know, that's another reason
for me not to like you.

1973
01:50:20,550 --> 01:50:23,954
That rum head spent 20 years in jail
for poisoning a kid.

1974
01:50:24,054 --> 01:50:26,915
If you know him,
you must be a jailbird yourself.

1975
01:50:27,015 --> 01:50:29,042
Would you show these gentlemen
to the door?

1976
01:50:29,142 --> 01:50:31,177
Sure. This way, gentlemen.

1977
01:50:36,600 --> 01:50:37,892
Stay out.

1978
01:50:39,061 --> 01:50:41,646
Get me! I'm giving out wings!

1979
01:50:44,316 --> 01:50:46,810
You see, George,
you were not there to stop Gower

1980
01:50:46,910 --> 01:50:48,603
from putting that poison
into the capsules.

1981
01:50:48,703 --> 01:50:52,365
What do you mean, I wasn't there?
I remember distinctly...

1982
01:50:54,577 --> 01:50:56,995
Hey, what's going on around here?

1983
01:50:57,246 --> 01:50:58,621
What...

1984
01:50:59,748 --> 01:51:02,417
Why, this ought to be Martini's place.

1985
01:51:08,299 --> 01:51:09,966
Look, who are you?

1986
01:51:10,217 --> 01:51:12,752
I told you, George.
I'm your guardian angel.

1987
01:51:12,852 --> 01:51:15,096
Yeah, yeah, I know. You told me that.

1988
01:51:20,686 --> 01:51:23,930
What else are you?
What, are you a hypnotist?

1989
01:51:24,030 --> 01:51:25,182
No. Of course not.

1990
01:51:25,282 --> 01:51:27,851
Well, then, why am I seeing
all these strange things here?

1991
01:51:27,951 --> 01:51:32,355
Don't you understand, George?
It's because you were not born.

1992
01:51:32,455 --> 01:51:36,735
- Well, if I wasn't born, who am I?
- You're nobody. You have no identity.

1993
01:51:36,835 --> 01:51:39,487
What do you mean, no identity?
My name's George Bailey.

1994
01:51:39,587 --> 01:51:41,623
There is no George Bailey.

1995
01:51:42,750 --> 01:51:47,085
You have no papers, no cards,
no driver's license,

1996
01:51:47,503 --> 01:51:50,255
no 4-F card, no insurance policy.

1997
01:51:51,257 --> 01:51:53,258
They're not there, either.

1998
01:51:54,469 --> 01:51:56,803
- What?
- Zuzu's petals.

1999
01:52:02,310 --> 01:52:05,020
You've been given a great gift, George,

2000
01:52:05,188 --> 01:52:08,815
a chance to see what the world
would be like without you.

2001
01:52:11,152 --> 01:52:13,779
Now, wait a minute here.
Wait a minute here.

2002
01:52:15,657 --> 01:52:18,992
This is some sort of a funny dream
I'm having.

2003
01:52:19,160 --> 01:52:20,945
So long, mister. I'm going home.

2004
01:52:21,045 --> 01:52:23,914
- Home? What home?
- Shut up! Cut it out!

2005
01:52:24,415 --> 01:52:28,460
You're crazy!
That's what I think. You're screwy.

2006
01:52:28,878 --> 01:52:31,580
You're driving me crazy, too.
I'm seeing things here.

2007
01:52:31,680 --> 01:52:33,582
I'm going home
and see my wife and family.

2008
01:52:33,682 --> 01:52:36,843
You understand that?
And I'm going home alone.

2009
01:52:39,222 --> 01:52:41,139
How am I doing, Joseph?

2010
01:52:41,849 --> 01:52:43,058
Thanks.

2011
01:52:43,393 --> 01:52:45,477
No, I didn't have a drink.

2012
01:53:36,696 --> 01:53:39,231
Hey, hey, where did
the Building and Loan move to?

2013
01:53:39,331 --> 01:53:40,316
Building and what?

2014
01:53:40,416 --> 01:53:42,151
The Bailey Building and Loan.
It was up there.

2015
01:53:42,251 --> 01:53:44,111
They went out of business years ago.

2016
01:53:44,211 --> 01:53:45,570
That sailor's a liar!

2017
01:53:45,670 --> 01:53:47,947
I know every big shot in this town!

2018
01:53:48,047 --> 01:53:50,575
I know Potter,
and I'll have you kicked off the beat.

2019
01:53:50,675 --> 01:53:52,126
Hey, Violet!

2020
01:53:53,337 --> 01:53:55,913
Hey, hey! Listen. That's Violet Bick.

2021
01:53:56,013 --> 01:53:58,124
- I know.
- I know that girl!

2022
01:53:58,224 --> 01:54:00,009
Take a walk. Beat it.

2023
01:54:02,012 --> 01:54:03,763
Hey, Ernie! Ernie.

2024
01:54:05,932 --> 01:54:07,842
Ernie, take me home.
I'm going off my nut.

2025
01:54:07,942 --> 01:54:08,926
Where do you live?

2026
01:54:09,026 --> 01:54:11,095
Now, doggone it, Ernie,
don't you start pulling that stuff.

2027
01:54:11,195 --> 01:54:13,681
You know where I live. 320 Sycamore.
Now hurry up.

2028
01:54:13,781 --> 01:54:17,226
- All right. 320 Sycamore?
- Yeah, yeah, hurry up. Zuzu's sick.

2029
01:54:17,326 --> 01:54:19,153
- Come on.
- All right. All right.

2030
01:54:19,780 --> 01:54:21,814
Come on, Ernie,
now straighten me out here.

2031
01:54:21,914 --> 01:54:24,901
Look, I've got some bad liquor
or something. Listen to me.

2032
01:54:25,001 --> 01:54:26,194
Now, you are Ernie Bishop,

2033
01:54:26,294 --> 01:54:28,029
and you live in Bailey Park
with your wife and kid?

2034
01:54:28,129 --> 01:54:30,156
- That's right, isn't it?
- You seen my wife?

2035
01:54:30,256 --> 01:54:33,493
Seen your wife?
I've been to your house 100 times.

2036
01:54:33,593 --> 01:54:36,371
Look, bud, what's the idea?
I live in a shack in Potter's Field,

2037
01:54:36,471 --> 01:54:38,498
my wife ran away three years ago
and took the kid,

2038
01:54:38,598 --> 01:54:41,042
and I ain't never seen you
before in my life, see?

2039
01:54:41,142 --> 01:54:43,928
Okay, well, just step on it.
Just get me home!

2040
01:55:01,446 --> 01:55:03,731
- Is this the place?
- Of course it's the place.

2041
01:55:03,831 --> 01:55:07,034
Well, this house ain't been lived in
for 20 years.

2042
01:55:13,083 --> 01:55:15,076
- What's up, Ernie?
- I don't know.

2043
01:55:15,176 --> 01:55:18,337
But we better keep our eye on this guy.
He's bats.

2044
01:55:35,814 --> 01:55:38,023
Mary. Mary!

2045
01:55:40,986 --> 01:55:43,863
Tommy! Pete! Janie! Zuzu!
Where are you?

2046
01:55:44,322 --> 01:55:46,940
They're not here, George.
You have no children.

2047
01:55:47,040 --> 01:55:48,442
Where are they?
What have you done with them?

2048
01:55:48,542 --> 01:55:50,694
All right, put up your hands.
No fast moves.

2049
01:55:50,794 --> 01:55:52,362
Come on out here, both of you.

2050
01:55:52,462 --> 01:55:54,781
- Bert! Thank heaven you're here.
- Back this.

2051
01:55:54,881 --> 01:55:58,118
Bert, what's happened to this house?
Where's Mary? Where's my kids?

2052
01:55:58,218 --> 01:55:59,870
- Watch him, Bert.
- Come on, come on.

2053
01:55:59,970 --> 01:56:01,997
Bert, Ernie.
What's the matter with you two guys?

2054
01:56:02,097 --> 01:56:03,582
You were here on my wedding night.

2055
01:56:03,682 --> 01:56:05,292
You, both of you,
stood out there on the porch

2056
01:56:05,392 --> 01:56:07,669
- and sung to us, don't you remember?
- Think I'd better be going.

2057
01:56:07,769 --> 01:56:09,087
Look, now, why don't you be a good kid,

2058
01:56:09,187 --> 01:56:10,297
and we'll take you in to a doctor?

2059
01:56:10,397 --> 01:56:12,340
- Everything's gonna be all right.
- Bert, no, listen to me.

2060
01:56:12,440 --> 01:56:14,301
Ernie, will you take me over
to my mother's house?

2061
01:56:14,401 --> 01:56:16,845
Bert, listen. It's that fellow here.
He says he's an angel.

2062
01:56:16,945 --> 01:56:20,398
- He's trying to hypnotize me.
- I hate to do this to you, bud, but...

2063
01:56:21,734 --> 01:56:24,444
Run, George! Run, George! Run!

2064
01:56:26,155 --> 01:56:28,948
- Joseph! Help! Help!
- Oh, shut up.

2065
01:56:29,074 --> 01:56:31,910
Oh, Joseph! Joseph!

2066
01:56:37,708 --> 01:56:41,002
Where'd he go? Where'd he go?
I had him right here.

2067
01:56:43,756 --> 01:56:45,298
I need a drink.

2068
01:56:45,758 --> 01:56:48,426
Well, which way did he go?
Help me find him.

2069
01:56:58,312 --> 01:56:59,437
Well?

2070
01:57:02,691 --> 01:57:03,900
Mother.

2071
01:57:05,903 --> 01:57:07,946
Mother? What do you want?

2072
01:57:09,114 --> 01:57:11,783
Mother, this is George.

2073
01:57:12,117 --> 01:57:13,902
I thought sure you'd remember me.

2074
01:57:14,002 --> 01:57:15,403
George who?

2075
01:57:15,503 --> 01:57:17,364
If you're looking for a room,
there's no vacancy.

2076
01:57:17,464 --> 01:57:20,784
Mother, listen. Please help me.
Something terrible's happened to me.

2077
01:57:20,884 --> 01:57:23,286
I don't know what it is.
Something's happened to everybody.

2078
01:57:23,386 --> 01:57:26,331
Please let me come in,
and keep me here until I get over it.

2079
01:57:26,431 --> 01:57:28,750
Get over what? I don't take in strangers

2080
01:57:28,850 --> 01:57:31,386
unless they're sent here
by somebody I know.

2081
01:57:31,720 --> 01:57:36,716
Well, I know everybody you know.
Your brother-in-law, Uncle Billy.

2082
01:57:36,816 --> 01:57:38,510
- You know him?
- Well, sure I do.

2083
01:57:38,610 --> 01:57:40,720
- When did you see him last?
- Today over at his house.

2084
01:57:40,820 --> 01:57:41,930
It's a lie.

2085
01:57:42,030 --> 01:57:44,891
He's been in the insane asylum
ever since he lost his business.

2086
01:57:44,991 --> 01:57:47,859
And if you ask me,
that's where you belong.

2087
01:57:59,789 --> 01:58:01,456
Strange, isn't it?

2088
01:58:01,916 --> 01:58:04,835
Each man's life
touches so many other lives.

2089
01:58:05,295 --> 01:58:08,247
And when he isn't around,
he leaves an awful hole, doesn't he?

2090
01:58:08,347 --> 01:58:09,498
I've heard of things like this.

2091
01:58:09,598 --> 01:58:11,333
You got me in some kind of a spell
or something.

2092
01:58:11,433 --> 01:58:13,502
Well, I'm gonna get out of it.
I'll get out of it.

2093
01:58:13,602 --> 01:58:15,387
I know how, too. I...

2094
01:58:15,805 --> 01:58:16,922
The last man I talked to,

2095
01:58:17,022 --> 01:58:19,174
before all this stuff
started happening to me, was Martini.

2096
01:58:19,274 --> 01:58:20,467
You know where he lives?

2097
01:58:20,567 --> 01:58:23,478
Well, sure, I know where he lives.
He lives in Bailey Park.

2098
01:58:27,066 --> 01:58:31,528
- Are you sure this is Bailey Park?
- No, I'm not sure of anything anymore.

2099
01:58:32,405 --> 01:58:35,240
All I know is this should be Bailey Park.

2100
01:58:36,034 --> 01:58:39,786
- But where are the houses?
- You weren't here to build them.

2101
01:58:44,375 --> 01:58:47,369
Your brother Harry Bailey
broke through the ice

2102
01:58:47,469 --> 01:58:49,330
and was drowned at the age of nine.

2103
01:58:49,430 --> 01:58:51,498
That's a lie. Harry Bailey went to war.

2104
01:58:51,598 --> 01:58:53,042
He got the Congressional
Medal of Honor.

2105
01:58:53,142 --> 01:58:55,085
He saved the lives
of every man on that transport.

2106
01:58:55,185 --> 01:58:57,212
Every man on that transport died.

2107
01:58:57,312 --> 01:58:58,631
Harry wasn't there to save them,

2108
01:58:58,731 --> 01:59:01,433
because you weren't there
to save Harry.

2109
01:59:12,612 --> 01:59:16,156
You see, George?
You really had a wonderful life.

2110
01:59:16,616 --> 01:59:20,702
Don't you see what a mistake
it would be to throw it away?

2111
01:59:21,371 --> 01:59:23,288
- Clarence.
- Yes, George?

2112
01:59:24,290 --> 01:59:27,493
- Where's Mary?
- Oh, well, I can't...

2113
01:59:27,593 --> 01:59:30,120
I don't know how you know these things,
but tell me, where is she?

2114
01:59:30,220 --> 01:59:32,164
If you know where she is,
tell me where my wife is.

2115
01:59:32,264 --> 01:59:35,250
- I'm not supposed to tell.
- Please, Clarence, tell me where she is.

2116
01:59:35,350 --> 01:59:37,670
- You're not gonna like it, George.
- Where is she?

2117
01:59:37,770 --> 01:59:40,089
She's an old maid. She never married.

2118
01:59:40,189 --> 01:59:42,508
Where is Mary? Where is she?
Where is she?

2119
01:59:42,608 --> 01:59:45,519
She's just about to close up the library!

2120
01:59:49,398 --> 01:59:52,775
There must be some easier way
for me to get my wings.

2121
02:00:04,287 --> 02:00:05,413
Mary!

2122
02:00:11,044 --> 02:00:12,128
Mary!

2123
02:00:14,548 --> 02:00:15,673
Mary!

2124
02:00:17,092 --> 02:00:18,634
Mary! Mary!

2125
02:00:18,802 --> 02:00:21,546
Mary, it's George. Don't you know me?
What's happened to us?

2126
02:00:21,646 --> 02:00:22,964
I don't know you. Let me go!

2127
02:00:23,064 --> 02:00:26,092
Mary, please! Oh, don't do this to me.
Please, Mary, help me.

2128
02:00:26,192 --> 02:00:28,352
Where's our kids? I need you, Mary.

